<HEADLINE> US to Harvest 9.31 Bln Bushels of Corn in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States is likely
to harvest some 9.31 billion bushels of corn this year, the
third-largest crop in history, the U.S. Agriculture Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The latest corn projection in October is 44 million bushels
higher than last month's forecast and 18 million bushels more than
the 1996 crop. This year's crop, if realized, will trail only the
1992 and 1994 corn harvests in size. One bushel of corn is
equivalent to 25.42 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The corn harvest was just beginning, with 15 percent of the
crop in as of October 5. Per-acre yields were expected to average
about 125.8 bushels per acre, down 1.3 bushels from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The department also projected that the soybean crop was
estimated at 2.72 billion bushels, down slightly from last month's
forecast but still 14 percent higher than the 1996 crop and still
an all-time record. One bushel of soybean is about 27.216
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Soybean yield on the 69.8 million planted acres was projected
at 39 bushels per acre, about 1.4 bushels more than last year.
</P>
<P>
Production of cotton was estimated at 18.4 million bales, down
3 percent from 1996 but still the fourth-largest crop in history.
Cotton yield was expected to average about 658 pounds per acre, a
drop of 49 pounds from last year. One bale of cotton is equal to
480 pounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
