<HEADLINE> Canadian FM Congratulates ICBL on Winning Nobel Peace Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy today congratulated the International
Campaign to Ban Land Mines (ICBL) and its coordinator Jody
Williams on the winning of the 1997 Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted at the Nobel Committee's choice and offer my
sincerest congratulations to Ms. William and all members of the
ICBL, including its Canadian member, Mines Action Canada,"
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
The ICBL has mobilized and empowered millions of citizens
worldwide with unprecedented speed and effectiveness, he said.
</P>
<P>
And the campaign has become a highly articulate moral and
diplomatic force with the field of international disarmament, the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
The ICBL has been in operation since 1992 and represents more
than 1,000 non-governmental organizations in over 60 countries.
</P>
<P>
Since May 1996, Canada has worked closely with the group to
help build a coalition of states and non-governmental
organizations that has resulted in an anti-personnel mines ban
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 countries are expected to come here and sign the
treaty in early December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
