<HEADLINE> US Wholesale Prices Up Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. inflation at the
wholesale level increased by a sharp 0.5 percent in September, the
fastest pace this year, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the gain in its Producer Price Index
(PPI), which measures cost pressures before they reach the
consumer, resulted mainly from big gains in the cost of energy,
new cars and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The gain, which followed a rise of 0.3 percent in August, was
more than double what investors had been expected.
</P>
<P>
The increase in U.S. wholesale prices last month reflected a
1.5 percent jump in energy prices, the biggest monthly gain since
December.
</P>
<P>
Food prices were up by a small 0.1 percent and reflected price
declines for beef, pork and poultry.
</P>
<P>
The 1.4 percent jump in new car prices was the biggest since
October 1994.
</P>
<P>
But even excluding the volatile food and energy sectors, the
so-called core rate of inflation was up 0.4 percent, the worst
showing since November 1995.
</P>
<P>
Wholesale prices in the U.S. so far this year are still falling
at an annual rate of 1.4 percent because the August and September
gains followed declines of seven straight months, something that
had never occurred since the U.S. government first began measuring
wholesale inflation in 1947.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) Chairman Alan Greenspan warned this
week that the economy's rapid growth and heavy demand for workers
were unsustainable and inflation continued to be the greatest
threat to ending the current recovery.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Greenspan's comments represented a change
from his generally optimistic summertime assessment of the current
U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
Many economists believe the U.S. Fed is poised to start
tightening credit further in the coming months. The Fed has left
interest rates unchanged since a small upward nudge in March,

nnnn
00:01 00:01 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
