<HEADLINE> France, Germany, Russia to Hold Annual Tripartite Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin announced today in Strasbourg,
France, that they will hold a summit with German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl once a year.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted Chirac as saying that a regular
tripartite summit meeting of France, Germany and Russia will make
up "an important force in Europe and notably a necessary element
for the deepening of peace."
</P>
<P>
Chirac half joked by suggesting the first such summit be held
in Sverdlovsk, now re-named Yekaterinburg in the Ural region of
Russia, which is Yeltsin's hometown.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Yeltsin were attending a meeting of the heads of
state or government of the European Council in the eastern French
city of Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Russia last month, Chirac suggested a
privileged partnership between Russia and the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
