<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Not Permit Illegally Employ Mozambicans: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government today
warned coffee and tea growers in the eastern highlands that they
risked prosecution should they continue to illegally employ
Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Minister for Public Service, Labour and Social Welfare
Florence Chitauro said that hundreds of Mozambicans are being
illegally employed as tea and coffee pluckers along Zimbabwe's
eastern border area.
</P>
<P>
''My ministry has not issued any
permit to any farmer to employ foreigners nor did the Home
Affairs Ministry. So i am saying it is illegal for the farmers to
employ a Mozambican without permit,'' Chitauro said.
</P>
<P>
She said illegal employment of foreigners meant that both
farmers and workers contributed nothing to the National Social
Security Scheme.
</P>
<P>
''Our foreign recruitment policy is very clear on this. we
only recruit foreigners in fields where locals do not have the
expertise,'' the minister stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
