<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Top Court Rules in Favor of Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's advocates for the
disabled were elated with a landmark Supreme Court ruling that
will help remove barriers impeding their full participation in
society.
</P>
<P>
The top court ruled Thursday that the British Columbia
provincial government's refusal to provide sign-language
interpreters violates the constitutional rights of the deaf to
equal benefit of the law guaranteed by the Charter of Rights and
Freedoms.
</P>
<P>
Governments are required by the charter to take reasonable
"positive steps" to ensure that disadvantaged groups are able to
benefit equally from services offered to the general public, the
court said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
They must go further and take "special measures" to get rid of
existing barriers for the disabled, it said.
</P>
<P>
Three people from the west province had sued the government
over the lack of sign-language interpreters for those receiving
medical services.
</P>
<P>
The B.C. government cut its funding for the service in 1990,
saying it would strain limited health care resources and create a
precedent for funding of similar services for the non-English
speaking immigrant community.
</P>
<P>
"It feels like 1989 and the Berlin Wall; the barriers are about
to start coming down," David Allen of the Canadian Hearing Society
was quoted by reports today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ruling will go beyond the deaf and will affect every
Canadian who has a disability, said David Baker of the Advocacy
Resource Center for the Handicapped.
</P>
<P>
"For Canadians with disabilities, this is unquestionably the
most important case ever," Baker said.
</P>
<P>
"I think people in Canada can expect to see more disabled
people in schools, throughout the health care system and in
employment," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
