<HEADLINE> More Children Suffer From Mental Ill-health in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Rising cases of child sexual
abuse, neglect and poverty are exposing a lot of Zimbabwean
children to mental health problems, Zimbabwe's first lady Grace
Mugabe said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the commemoration of World Mental Health Day in
Harare, Mugabe said mental health problems of children and
adolescents in the country are real and very painful.
</P>
<P>
"The government has recognized the impact of mental health
problems of children in the country, especially with the upsurge
in sexual abuse and rise in numbers of street children," she
said.
</P>
<P>
This year's World Mental Health Day is commemorated under the
theme "children and mental health".
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said policies needed to be formulated to address the
problems of street children to protect them from malnutrition,
sexual abuse and violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local psychiatrist Fidglis Chikara said the mental
health provided in the country is inadequate as there are only 11
psychiatrists for the country's 12 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
