<HEADLINE> Suspected 1986 Berlin Disco Attacker Extradited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A Libyan national suspected of a
link with the 1986 deadly bombing of a Berlin discotheque today
was extradited to Germany six weeks after being arrested in Italy,
local press reported here.
</P>
<P>
Musbah Eter, 40, fleeing Berlin last July after a warrant for
his arrest was issued, is accused of building the explosive device
which blew up on April 5, 1986 at the LaBella discotheque
frequented by U.S. soldiers, killing three people and injuring 260
others.
</P>
<P>
He will stand trial in Berlin on November 18 on charge of
involvement in the attack, along with three other defendants --
Palestinian Yassir Chraidi, Ali Chanaa, a German national, and his
ex-wife Verena, who are all on charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan secret service was said to have plotted the 1986
attack in the discotheque, which was mainly visited by
U.S. soldiers stationed in west Berlin. But the Libyan government
has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
In revenge, Washington ordered air strikes against the Libyan
cities of Tripoli and Benghazi in which dozens of people were
killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
