<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brundtland Vying for Post of WHO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Former Norwegian Prime Minister
Gro Harlem Brundtland, who is vying for the post of Director
General of the World Health Organization, said here today if
elected, she will strive to improve health conditions in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland who paid a courtesy call on Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, said although health problems are a world wide
issue, real challenges lay in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The real challenges lie in Africa, especially in the fight
against malaria which kills an average of two million people
every year, not to add the problem of AIDS which is more
prevalent. There is need for more primary health care in Africa
followed by maybe Asia than anywhere else in the world," said
Brundtland.
</P>
<P>
She said if appointed, she will base her leadership on the
firm belief that a healthy and well-educated population is every
country's greatest resource.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland also commended WHO Regional Director for Africa
Ibrahim Malick Samba, who was endorsed by the Organization of
African Unity as a candidate, for having done well enough to
command respect in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Brundtland said after her visit to southern African states,
she will tour Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
