<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approves State Pension Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- German parliament today approved a
bill to reduce state retirement pensions from the present 70 percent
of average net wages to 64 percent in stages during the period from
the year 2015 to 2030.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by the Bundestag, the lower house of parliament,
was opposed by main opposition Social Democrats (SPD), which, holding
a majority in the upper house, the Bundesrat, was however unable to
block the reform.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government intends to keep the monthly
pension fund payments at its current level of 20.3 percent of wages or
salaries, but contributions would rise to 20.8 percent next year
unless being further subsidized by the government.
</P>
<P>
The government considers raising value added tax (VAT) to 16
percent from the current level of 15 percent to boost revenue and
avert an increase in pension contributions. SPD has vowed to use its
majority in the Bundesrat to block the plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
