<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Visit Ukraine in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
will pay a state visit to Ukraine next year, probably in summer,
announced a French presidential spokesperson today in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma were attending the
second summit of heads of state or government of the 40-member
Council of Europe, which is Europe's largest forum, held today in
the eastern French city.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed the joint development of the Antonov
transport planes by Ukraine, Russia, France and Germany, according
to Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Chirac called on Ukraine to continue its structural reforms,
and to adopt "transparent and stable legislation in the field of
investment and tax," said AFP.
</P>
<P>
The French president also asked Ukraine to make sure that the
Chernobyl nuclear reaction center, whose reactor exploded in 1986,
be closed before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), Jacques de Larosiere, had
promised him to respect the commitment of the bank in helping
Ukraine strengthen the sarcophagus around the nuclear center.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma complained that the EBRD is too slow in realizing its
engagements for Chernobyl.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven (G-7) most industrialized nations has
agreed to donate 300 million US dollars in reinforcing the
sarcophagus around the Chernobyl reaction center via the EBRD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland to Welcome Likely "Bloody Sunday" Apology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government has
indicated that it would welcome an apology from the British
government on the so-called "Bloody Sunday" incident in which 14
unarmed Catholic nationalists were killed.
</P>
<P>
Senior British government sources were quoted by today's Times
newspaper as saying that Britain would set up an independent
review to examine fresh evidence on the incident, paving the way
for a formal apology.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the press report, Ireland's new Foreign Minister
David Andrews said that the Irish government would be delighted at
such a positive response.
</P>
<P>
"I do think an apology would be welcome and I think it would be
helpful in the (Northern Ireland) peace process," he told the BBC
Radio.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the Dublin government gave Britain's Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam some new evidence about the incident,
largely based on two television documentaries and a book
containing eyewitness accounts.
</P>
<P>
On "Bloody Sunday" -- January 30, 1972, British paratroopers
shot dead 14 Catholic men during a civil rights demonstration in
Londondery, Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
