<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Rules Out Replacement for Britannia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson announced today that Britain's world-famous Royal Yacht
Britannia will not be refitted; nor will she be replaced after
being decommissioned in December.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said in a statement which ended months of controversy
about the yacht's future that the government is looking at options
for Britannia's future, including turning it into a heritage
center, floating museum or corporate hospitality center.
</P>
<P>
The yacht, once a potent symbol of the British Empire, will
begin a final round-Britain voyage from Portsmouth on October 20.
</P>
<P>
The Queen and many other members of the royal family will board
the yacht for the final leg of her tour from London to Portsmouth
where the decommissioning ceremony will be held on December 11.
</P>
<P>
The statement followed Chancellor Gordon Brown's announcement
last week that it was "very difficult" to justify spending
millions of pounds of public money on a new yacht.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the decision was backed by the royal
family which is anxious to avoid any accusations of extravagance.
</P>
<P>
The 44-year-old Britannia has circumnavigated the globe eight
times and taken the royal family on almost 700 overseas visits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Announces Plan for 35-Hour Working Week Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin announced today that he will present a draft law on
reducing legal working week time to 35 hours as of January 1,
2000, for all companies with more than 10 workers in France.
</P>
<P>
The government will also offer companies 9,000 francs (1,500 US
dollars) for employing one worker in 1998, while reducing working
week time by at least 10 percent and increasing the number of
staff by at least 6 percent, said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement at the end of a job conference held in
his office building today and attended by representatives of
entrepreneurs, trade union leaders and government officials.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the reduction of working time depends on a
controlled increase of jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
To cut working week time to 35 hours is part of the major
legislative campaign promises made by Jospin before he and his
Socialist Party obtained power by beating the central-right
coalition in the early legislative elections held in May and June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
