<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Calls for an End to Teachers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today directed government officials to immediately meet with
the Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT) in order to seek a
solution to the teachers' salary dispute.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a mass rally marking this year's Moi Day, the
president asked Head of the Public Service Fares Kuindwa and
other officials to report to him the results of their talks with
KNUT within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
In view of the new development of the on-going teachers strike
which started on October 1, the president directed that the
dispute be withdrawn immediately from the Industrial Court.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that his government has always been concerned about
the welfare of the public servants and wishes the salary dispute
to be "resolved amicably" and a return-to-work-formula found.
</P>
<P>
On October 6, a meeting between the government and the KNUT
reached a deadlock, with the teachers' union vowing to continue
with the strike until the government meets its demands.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Education Minister Joseph Kamotho ordered all
striking teachers to report to their schools by 8 a.m. on October
8.
</P>
<P>
As the teachers union vowed to ignore the education minister's
ultimatum, the Kenyan government referred the salary dispute back
to the Industrial Court on October 7.
</P>
<P>
The teachers are demanding a salary increase ranging between
150 and 200 percent for the 240,000 primary and secondary school
teachers in the country, but the government agreed to a 10-28
percent increase and allowance increment of between 15 and 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Labour Minister Philip Masinde said that the government
can not meet the demands by the teachers' union, noting that
higher salaries will amount to about 1.4 billion U.S. Dollars a
year, or 56 percent of the total government revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beats Kuwait 2-1 at World Cup Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Gao Feng's last minute goal gave
China a 2-1 win over Kuwait in a match A of the Asian World Cup
soccer qualification tournament here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The tow sides tied 1-1 at the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
At the third minute, China's top striker Hao Haidong blasted
the ball into the left corner of the net with turnaround shot
after connecting a pass at the top of the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
Chinese goalkeeper Ou Chuliang then made several brilliant
saves including the one he palmed out a close shot by unmarked
Esam M. Sakeen.
</P>
<P>
At the 25th minute, Jassem M. Houwaidi netted his third goal in
his fourth match, putting the score at one-all.
</P>
<P>
Houwaidi lobbed the ball into an open net as Ou ran out in a
desperate attempt to dispossess the Kuwaiti top striker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tories Will "Conquer" Labor at Next Election: Hague </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Opposition leader William Hague
condemned the "cynicism" of Labor today by saying that the Tories
are the "only party of principle."
</P>
<P>
In his first party conference speech as party leader, Hague
said Labor's "policies without conscience" would "ultimately breed
contempt."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Tories had to rediscover its tolerant, caring
heart and embark on "a process of reform and renewal" that would
prepare for a return to power at the next election.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader also made a public apology for former
Prime Minister Margret Thatcher's decision to take Britain into
the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM).
</P>
<P>
"I'm sorry we did it," he told the conference which ended
today. "We should have the courage and the confidence to say so.
It did enormous damage to the credibility of our party and we paid
the price."
</P>
<P>
It was in 1990 that the former prime minister took the pound
into the ERM with Hague's predecessor John Major as her
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
In September 1992, it was Major, then as prime minister, who
desperately tried to defend the pound, raising interest rates to
15 percent, before Britain was finally ejected from the ERM.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Hague's penance was deliberately
designed to help the party to cleanse its past failures and move
on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
