<HEADLINE> S. African Mining Giants to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South African mining
giants, Gencor and Gold Fields, are planning to merge their gold
operations in a bid to take the lead in global gold mining
industry, the South African Press Association SAPA said today.
</P>
<P>
The two groups intended to combine their gold operating
companies, exploration assets and mineral rights into Goldco, a
focused and autonomous gold mining group, SAPA quoted
unidentified senior officials of the groups as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The deal would link three of the world's premier mining
operations, Driefontein, Kloof and Beatrix, and would boast
output of more than four million ounces of gold per year.
</P>
<P>
The new company would have total minerable reserves of
approximately 120-million ounces, making it the largest gold
group in terms of equity accounted reserves.
</P>
<P>
Gencor Chairman Brian Gilbertson has initially been appointed
chairman of Goldco, and will take up a non-executive position of
joint deputy chairman of Gold Fileds, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Gilbertson said the merger would create one of the largest and
the most exciting gold companies in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
