<HEADLINE> Canada, Russia to Enhance Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Russia have agreed to
hold talks on measures that will increase two-way trade by the
year 2000, Canada's International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"These consultations, due to begin by the end of 1997, will
also examine measures to accelerate Russian integration into world
markets," Marchi said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the Third Annual Canada-Russia
Intergovernmental Economic Commission, which took place here
today.
</P>
<P>
Marchi and visiting Russian Deputy Prime Minister Valery Serov
co-chaired the commission's plenary session.
</P>
<P>
They also witnessed the signing of a 16-million U.S. dollar
contract for housing components for Russia's Sakhalin Island.
</P>
<P>
Local contractors in Sakhalin will use the components to build
800 housing units for victims of a 1995 earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two governments agreed to seek ways to make
available additional export financing, backed by Russian sovereign
guarantees, for priority investment development projects. 
</P>
