<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jody Williams Wins 1997 Nobel Peace Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Jody Williams, the
coordinator of the International Campaign to Ban Landmines, has
been awarded the 1997 Nobel Peace Prize for her efforts to
eradicate antipersonnel landmines, said a press release issued
today by the spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
Judy Williams, 47, began working for the Vietnam Veterans of
American Foundation at the end of 1991 to bring together a
coalition to ban international landmines. From two organizations,
the coalition has grown to more than 1,000 non-governmental
organizations in over 60 countries working together as the
International Campaign to Ban Landmines.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Williams has spoken extensively all over the globe on the
issue of the landmines crisis and its only solution: an
international treaty to ban the weapon. She has also written
extensively about the issue on the socio-economic impact of the
weapon.
</P>
<P>
Upon graduation from the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced
International Studies, she coordinated the Nicaragua-Honduras
education project which organized and led fact-finding delegations
of US opinion makers to Central America.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation with Ms. Williams, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan conveyed his congratulations to her
by saying that it was a really well-deserved honor and it also
showed that the world had come together, civil societies and
non-governmental organizations had come together and worked with
governments.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the world had achieved a major achievement which was
a victory for every child and mother and all vulnerable societies
in these conflicts areas who had been killed or maimed by these
silent weapons. He urged all governments to sign the landmines on
banning landmines in Ottawa in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria in Fresh Row with Britain over Visa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- While the row over a bilateral
air traffic ban remains unsolved between Nigeria and Britain, a
new dispute on visa issues has emerged to accentuate the already
frosty relations.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has condemned as "unjustified and unacceptable" the
practice of stamping, marking or annotating the passport of
rejected visa applicants by the British High Commission, and
urged the commission to discontinue the practice.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria today, British High
Commissioner Graham Burton was summoned from Lagos to the
foreign ministry in the capital Abuja on Wednesday to hear the
complaints.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi told Burton that the British
Embassy should also refund the visa fees collected from
unsuccessful applicants since June this year and forward to the
ministry the inventory of all visa applications from the same
month.
</P>
<P>
The issue was first raised by Jibrin Chinade, director-general
of the ministry, in June this year when he accused the British
and United States embassies of treating Nigerian visa applicants
with disrespect.
</P>
<P>
He described the 75 percent visa rejection as "extremely high"
and contended that the mutilation not only contradicted the
practice by Nigerian embassies, but stigmatized such applicants
and jeopardized their chances in other embassies.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinade, foreign embassies in Nigeria earned
about three billion Naira (about 36 million U.S. Dollars) from
visa fees last year.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent reaction to Nigeria's demand for refunding visa
fees to unsuccessful applicants, the British embassy said on
Thursday it was the policy of the country to recover the full
cost of processing visas all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The British side explained that the fee was used to meet
administrative costs incurred in processing the application,
whether or not a visa was issued.
</P>
<P>
The British embassy said in a statement that its offices in
Lagos and Abuja "process between 100 and 400 new visa
applications each day, depending on the time of the year".
</P>
<P>
Last year, 83 percent of applicants received visas and 61
percent of all applicants were issued visa within 24 hours, it
said, adding, "monthly statistics give no reason to believe that
those percentages will be significantly different for the current
year."
</P>
<P>
The relations between Nigeria and Britain became cold in 1993
when a presidential election was annulled on charges of
malpractice. It got to the bottom following the military
government executed nine minority activists two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Britain was in the forefront of demanding the suspension of
Nigeria's Commonwealth membership at that time.
</P>
<P>
While no soft-pedaling was witnessed in the new British
government's policy toward Nigeria as speculated, aviation
authorities of the country ordered a ban last May on all
Nigeria-registered aircraft to enter its airspace.
</P>
<P>
The action met an immediate retaliation when Nigeria announced
a similar ban the following day.
</P>
<P>
With the British Airways suffering an estimated loss of more
than 80 million U.S. Dollars for ticket revenue alone since the
impasse, Britain held out the olive branch and lifted the ban in
August.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian aviation authorities, however, have kept silence
and the impasse still remains.
</P>
<P>
To date, there is no sign in sight as for when and how the
rift between the two countries could be closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Agrees to Stop Using Canadian Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada said today that Israel
has agreed to stop using Canadian passports in covert operations.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy told
parliament that he got the assurance from his Israeli counterpart,
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
In a diplomatic letter received today, Levy apologized "for the
fact that any misuse of our passports may have caused
inconvenience or any problems of safety for any Canadian citizen,"
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
"Israel will now undertake measures to ensure it never happens
again," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Canada recalled its ambassador to Israel to protest the use of
forged Canadian passports by two Israeli agents, who carried out
an attack in Jordan on Khaled Meshal, political chief of the
militant Islamic group Hamas, on September 25.
</P>
<P>
Apparently, the letter was sent here in a bid to calm Canada's
outrage over the passport incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
