<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Grow 3.5 Pct in 1997: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Bank of Canada
predicted today that the Canadian economy will grow 3.5 percent
this year and 3.3 percent next year, ahead of other industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
The bank, the largest commercial one in Canada, made the
forecast in a media briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
Canada's growth this year will continue to be led by
construction and manufacturing, according to John McCallum, chief
economist of the bank.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, exports of vehicles, metals, electrical and
electronic products will remain healthy, he said.
</P>
<P>
The low interest rates, an improving job market and rising
consumer confidence will continue to have positive impacts on the
economy, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, an Ottawa-based economic think-tank, the
Conference Board of Canada, predicted a 3.4-percent growth for the
country's economy this year and 3.1 percent next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
