<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Fighting in S. Leone Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- There were reports of more
fightings today just outside the Sierra Leonean capital of
Freetown, the British Broadcasting Corporation said.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the fightings was on a Nigerian-held army base in
a suburban town with reports of shellings and casualty, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
No casualty figures were released however.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Nigerian-led west African peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) bombed the military headquarters of the junta,
which seized power in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG statement also said the force destroyed one of the
junta's helicopter gunship to retaliate the attack on ECOMOG
positions by the junta.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG is carrying out the mission of enforcing embargo
ordered by west African leaders as a means to force the junta to
hand over power to the legitimate government it overthrew.
</P>
<P>
In what appeared as a retaliatory action, soldiers loyal to
the junta burned down the personal house of ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in Freetown on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
But the junta reportedly denied the burning, saying the damage
was done by Sierra Leonean youths opposed to the deposed
president, who has stayed in neighboring Guinea since the coup.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Nigeria Television Authority
tonight, the junta has sought dialogue with President Kabbah on
the stand that "the situation in the country is strictly
internal".
</P>
<P>
So far no reply has been heard from President Kabbah, who just
return from New York where he addressed the United Nations
Assembly to seek support of the international community for
restoring democracy in his country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council passed a resolution on Wednesday on
oil, weapon and travel sanctions against Sierra Leone, which is
seen as the strongest backing Kabbah has received at the moment.
</P>
<P>
President Kabbah arrived in Nigeria Wednesday night and is
expected to take part in the meeting of the west African
Committee of Five on the crisis of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is scheduled for the Nigerian capital of Freetown
today and expected to discuss the new situation arising from the
U.N. sanctions. But no report of it has been available at press
time.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Guinea, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire and Liberia are members
of the committee set up at the order of the authority of the
Economic Community of West African States in the wake of the
coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
