<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches Information Technology Awareness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today launched a national information technology
(IT) awareness campaign, saying his government adopted IT as the
nation's number one priority.
</P>
<P>
"Through placing IT at the center stage of our socio-economic
development and planning, we are in fact attempting to adjust to a
new age," he said in his nationwide address tonight on radio and
television.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir described IT as the base of a new revolution of global
magnitude now in process, "accelerating the process of
globalization, reshaping our economy, and affecting our work and
life at a speed never seen before".
</P>
<P>
He said "To provide us the direction and the way forward with
IT, we have developed the National IT Agenda, or NITA, which
provides the framework for a national response to IT and to the
information revolution."
</P>
<P>
The NITA focuses on three elements crucial to the evolution of
the noble society: people development, info-structure (both hard
and soft infrastructure) development, and applications
development.
</P>
<P>
The NITA calls upon all Malaysians to do his or her part in
making sure that Malaysia is ready to enter the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of the NITA is to evolve a civil society in
the Malaysian mold, a society that is empowered by knowledge and
infused with its own distinctive value-system.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said "It is the knowledge-rich and value-creating
society that will boost our national productivity to higher levels
and ensure our economical survival. It is also this society that
will become mature, liberal, democratic, tolerant, caring and
economically just."
</P>
<P>
He said "our future economic competitiveness will depend upon
our willingness to harness IT and become knowledge workers.
Through the use of information and knowledge we can increase not
only our productivity, but also the quality of our products and
services as well."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was of the view that only when both manufacturing and
service sectors are manned by knowledge workers and powered by IT
can Malaysia expect to sustain the required per capita GDP growth
rates that will enable the country to attain Vision 2020, that is
a goal to be a developed nation by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
"With our future at stake we cannot afford to be a mere
spectator of the information revolution. We need to be a part of
it; we need to lead it even. This is why we are spending so much
time and effort to grow a local IT industry that is world-class.
This is also why, despite the recent currency crisis, the
MSC(Multimedia Super Corridor) projects will proceed as planned,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The MSC project which embodies the three elements of NITA is a
program to bring together the world's best IT and multimedia
companies into Malaysia to help it create and develop applications
that are culturally compatible with the various cultures of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said "Malaysia is in a good position to take advantage
of IT. We have 25 years of experience in developing a formidable
electrical and electronics industry. We have a well-educated and
trainable work force and our IT infrastructure is relatively
well-developed. No doubt there is more to be done before we can
take full advantage of IT, but these are all positive factors that
can propel the country towards a new trajectory of growth."
</P>
<P>
He said that a nation must always think about tomorrow. It is
in thinking about tomorrow that Malaysia has decided to harness
the power of IT, committing his government to an active role in
pursuing this endeavor by not only providing the necessary
top-down leadership to promote IT development, but also
orchestrating a societal push for it.
</P>
<P>
Urging Malaysians to support the nation's initiative in
harnessing IT, the president said "Let us resolve to face the
globalized world together. Let us strive to realize all that we
wish for and not wait for it to happen." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0053 </DOCNO>
