<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Launches Environmental Campaign in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The international environmental
group Greenpeace is organizing a campaign of environmental
awareness to draw attention to the dangers of industrial
pollution threatening the Lebanese coast.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace Lebanon is preparing a coastal tour to collect
random samples from the sea, groundwater, river beds, aquifers
and known industrial outflows, Lebanese newspaper Beirut Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Fouad Hamdan, the Lebanese Greenpeace representative, said that
the current campaign is aimed at raising environmental awareness
of industrial pollution amongst industrialists, government
authorities and the public at large.
</P>
<P>
Teams of researchers and scientists will be carrying out
in-depth research of industrial pollution.
</P>
<P>
Journalists and media representatives will also be invited
to inform the public of the result of their findings, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The environmental pollution in Lebanon has long been a subject
of concern. According to figures available, every year Lebanese
industries generate 325,000 tonnes of refuse and industrial waste,
much of it toxic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
