<HEADLINE> Egypt to Send Agricultural Experts to Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will dispatch its
agricultural experts to a number of developing countries to shore
up south-south cooperation on fighting hunger and securing food,
the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said today.
</P>
<P>
Michael Hage, information officer of FAO's Cairo-based Near
East Office, made the remarks following a series of meetings FAO
Director-General Jacques Diouf held today with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Minister of
Agriculture Youssef Wali.
</P>
<P>
Diouf will leave Egypt for Turkey today, wrapping up a
three-day visit, to attend the International Forest Conference,
due to start in Ankara Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moussa and Diouf discussed the dispatch of Egyptian
agricultural experts to Azerbaijan and Turkmenistan within the
framework of the food security and cooperation program among the
countries of the south, Hage said.
</P>
<P>
They also tackled the possibility of Egypt's cooperation with
the FAO, through the Egyptian Fund for Technical Cooperation in
Africa, to help Tanzania implement a major project on food
security, he said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing reporters following his meeting with Mubarak, Diouf
played up the potentials for Egypt to increase its agricultural
land and expand cooperation with other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke of the importance of preventing the use of food
as a pressure card in international politics.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, during the meeting, called for furthering efforts to
lessen the number of the hunger-stricken people around the globe,
put at 800 million, said the FAO chief.
</P>
<P>
Diouf said his meeting with Mubarak covered ways of realizing
the aim of halving the number of undernourished people by 2015, a
commitment pledged by 186 countries at the 1996 World Food
Summit, and FAO's relevant strategy.
</P>
<P>
Under a special program for food security, the FAO is helping
the low-income food-deficit countries, faced with food
shortfalls, limited funds to finance imports and declining food
aid, to increase food production and productivity quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
