<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 200 Land Law Protesters Arrested in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 farmers have been
arrested since October 1 when a controversial land law took effect
in Egypt, according to a report of the Land Center for Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
Since then, two people have been killed and dozens injured in
the northern Delta in a wave of violence over the landmark law
that reforms the tenant-landowner relationship, Middle East Times
in its latest edition quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
One tenant farmer was shot dead by a landowner who tried to
evict him from his land and a 14-year-old girl was killed during a
battle between the families of a landowner and his tenant,
according to the Land Center.
</P>
<P>
A third man died of "physical shock" caused by his landlord's
refusal to renew his tenancy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since June, tension in rural Egypt has been mounting and there
have been violent clashes and sporadic arrests of both tenant
farmers and peasant advocates in 10 governorates over the
prospects that landlords are able to raise rents or evict tenants.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was passed in 1992 with a five-year grace
period, completely does away with land rent controls that have
been in place since the 1952 revolution.
</P>
<P>
The law ordains that between 1992 and October 1 1997,
rents be increased to 22 times the amount of tax paid by the
landowner, leaving it up to the owner and tenant to agree on new
rents after that.
</P>
<P>
From 1952 to 1992, land rents were locked at seven times the
land tax, which averaged 30 to 35 pounds (about 9 to 11
U.S. dollars) annually per feddan.
</P>
<P>
A total of 17 people are reportedly to have been killed, more
than 300 wounded and nearly 1,000 detained since protests against
the law began in January.
</P>
<P>
Most incidents of violence and clashes with the police took
place in early July, when tenant farmers tried to burn down the
local offices of the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of unrest after the law came into effect,
Egyptian security services have deployed reinforcements throughout
villages in Upper Egypt, according to local newspapers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calm Returns After Fighting in Somali Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Reports from the
Southwestern town of Baidoa indicate that calm has returned
to the town today following two days of fierce fighting between
the forces of Hussein Mohamed Aidid and those of the Rahanwein
Resistance Army (RRA).
</P>
<P>
According to commuters from the town of Baidoa who
reached Mogadishu today, heavily armed militiamen with dozens of
battle wagons have been guarding all main check points inside the
town and the roads linking Baidoa to Mogadishu of Huddor town
over the control of the town and its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
Commuters said the militiamen spoke with nobody but showed
extra alertness.
</P>
<P>
Here in Mogadishu, some of the main commercial VHF radios in
relation with Baidoa town have been operating with dozens of
people trying to reach the town to enquire about either their
relatives or friends in the town and its surrounding villages.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from the VHF radios, the business
activities remain stuck with the main market and the elementary
shops closed in fear of another fighting.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the ordinary public transport buses between
Mogadishu and Baidoa are yet to start their business for safety
related precautions.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by the South Mogadishu faction leader,
Hussein Mohamed Aidid remains in Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
A number war wounded militiamen from Hussein Aidid's side have
reached Mogadishu for treatment last night. At least 19 people
have died and more than a dozen others were wounded during the
fighting for the past two days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
