<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economic Reforms to Continue: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe today promised visiting German investors that his country
will continue with economic reforms in order to improve
the investment climate.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said this when he met visiting Chairman of the Southern
African Initiative of German business (Safri) Juergen Schrempp
in Harare.
</P>
<P>
"We are carrying on with economic reforms and we are still
improving on these reforms so that we can attract more investors. We
have done quite a lot already over the past few years to improve our
environment," Mugabe told Schrempp, the chief executive of Damiler
Benz, who is in Zimbabwe on Safri business.
</P>
<P>
Safri is a project of German businesses aimed at strengthening
relations with Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Schrempp said that he was optimistic that the country's
economy and that of the entire Southern African Development
Community would continue to improve.
</P>
<P>
He was however worried about bureaucratic delays which in some
cases hindered investment into the country.
</P>
<P>
He said his discussions with Mugabe centered on investment
opportunities in Zimbabwe and the changes that have taken place in
the country since the last German-Zimbabwe investment conference in
Hamburg last year.
</P>
<P>
The German business executive who has already visited South Africa
and Namibia and is on his way to Mozambique, said he was happy with
the economic growth of the whole region. 
</P>
