<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Free Zone Exports Increase by 30 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Exports from Egypt's free zones
have been on the rise at a solid pace, registering a 30 percent
growth in the first nine months this year over the same period
last year, according to the General Investment Authority.
</P>
<P>
Exports amounted to 284.5 million dollars by September as
opposed to 219.5 million dollars by September last year, head of
the authority Ibrahim Fawzi said.
</P>
<P>
This sum represents 19 percent of Egypt's annual industrial
exports that are estimated at 1.5 billion dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
In September 1997 alone, free zones exports increased by 58
percent against the same month in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
The figures represent the net export and do not include
supplies to ships, transit or handling among various areas, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt ushered in its first free trade zone in the early 1970s
and since then has built six in Cairo, Alexandria, Ismailia,
Port Said, Suez and Domiette. Another three are under construction.
</P>
<P>
Products manufactured in these free trade zones include
ready-made clothes, chemical products, food and building
materials, are solely for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
