<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Bank Loans Increase 22 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Macao Daily News reported today that most of the loan
increases were on such sectors as individual credit, construction
and public engineering.
</P>
<P>
The credit to industrial sectors began picking up in late June
following a consecutive drop since the second quarter of 1995, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the first quarter of this year, the increase of
loans in the second quarter on individual credit rose by the
largest margin of 830 million patacas (about 105 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Among the increase, the credit on real estate mortgage deal
rose some 200 million patacas (about 25.3 million U.S. dollars),
showing a recovery of the real estate industry, which is one of
the pillar sector of the Macao economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Macao banks increased loans to the manufacturing
sector in the second quarter. By the end of June, the loans
climbed 11.1 percent as compared with that of the first three
months. More than half of the increase went to textile and garment
factories.
</P>
<P>
Observers noticed that the export of textile and garment
products has mounted to over 80 percent of all exports in
Macao. It kept rising over the first eight months.
</P>
<P>
But the report said that decreases were also registered in bank
loans to such sectors as electricity, gas fuel and water works,
transportation, warehousing and telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
