<HEADLINE> HKSAR Electoral Body Solicits Views on Constituency Delimitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Electoral Affairs
Commission of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
today called on all the local citizens to voice their opinions as
soon as possible over its recommendations on the geographical
delineation of constituencies for the forthcoming legislative
elections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference to launch a two-week public
consultation on the recommendations, the commission's chairman,
Justice Woo Kwok-Hing, stated that the deadline was set for
October 24. It means all the SAR citizens should put forward their
views by the fixed day.
</P>
<P>
To run concrete affairs related to the elections of the first
SAR Legislative Council scheduled for May 1998, the three-member
commission was established on September 29. Its two other members
are Norman Leung Nai-pang, deputy-chairman of the City Bus Group
Limited, and Elizabeth SC Shing, director general of the Hong Kong
Management Association.
</P>
<P>
Woo told reporters that his commission would take into account
the public views expressed when compiling its final
recommendations. "The final recommendations are expected to be
submitted to Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa by the statutory
deadline on October 31, 1997," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the five legislative Council Constituency
Areas proposed by the commission, namely Hong Kong Island, Kowloon
West, Kowloon East, "New Territories" West and "New Territories"
East, were formed by appropriate grouping of the 346 District
Board Constituency Areas.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that in deciding on the electoral boundaries, the
commission has maintained its apolitical stance.
</P>
<P>
"Matters relating to maintaining political influence or
advantage are not only irrelevant considerations for the
commission, but the commission should avoid even giving any
semblance of favoring any one politician or political party as
against others," Woo said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public to come forward and make known their views,
whether supportive or dissenting. But they should state their
opinions with full reason, he pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
