<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts to Meet on Status of African Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Four United Nations
agencies will hold a one-week experts meeting on adolescent girls
and their rights, said a press release issued by the U.N. Economic
Commission for Africa (ECA) today.
</P>
<P>
The experts meeting, which will be held from October 13 to 17
here, is obliged to prepare a report on the status of African
women to be submitted to the next ECA session in march 1998.
</P>
<P>
the experts meeting, organized jointly by the ECA, United
Nations Division for the Advancement of Women (DAW), the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA).
</P>
<P>
Adolescent girl child is defined as a girl between the ages of
10 and 15, and is one of the 12 critical areas of concern in the
Beijing Platform For Action, adopted by the Fourth World
Conference on Women held in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
The platform underlines that ''Discrimination and neglect in
childhood can initiate a life-long downward spiral of deprivation
and exclusion from the social mainstream''. It recommends that
''initiatives be taken to prepare girls to participate actively,
effectively and equally with boys at all levels of social,
economic, political and cultural leadership.''
</P>
<P>
The press release said that the experts meeting will examine
various aspects of the situation of adolescent girls and their
rights. The experts will make recommendations for accelerating
the implementation of the Beijing Platform For Action, it added.
</P>
<P>
Experts from governmental as well as non-governmental organs,
academia and research institutions are scheduled to attend the
one-week meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
