<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oracle Bone Inscriptions Exhibition Held in East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese
calligraphers working with oracle bones exhibited their
works for the first time in Nanjing Friday.
</P>
<P>
Oracle bone inscriptions, the earliest writing discovered in
China, were carved on tortoise shells and the bones of animals.
</P>
<P>
Research of oracle bone inscriptions has been an independent
international discipline since their discovery at the end of the
19th century.
</P>
<P>
Scholars in more than 10 countries and regions are currently
studying the ancient Chinese legacy, with Chinese and Japanese
scholars offering great contributions.
</P>
<P>
Some 118 works of oracle bone inscriptions, including 92
Chinese and 26 Japanese inscriptions, have been on show in various
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the exhibitions will be extremely important for
promoting further research into oracle bone inscriptions in the
coming new century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
