<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feelings Vary in Cost Estimates of NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Feelings were mixed when NATO
parliamentarians today started figuring out the discrepancies
among various enlargement cost estimates.
</P>
<P>
For politicians and economists, the lower price tag, which has
been forecast to last at least 12 years, was good news, while
defense industrialists preferred a higher price.
</P>
<P>
When the U.S. Congressional Budget Office first published its
estimate in March 1996, its prediction of 60.6--125 billion U.S.
dollars immediately became a target of sharp criticism from
politicians and economists.
</P>
<P>
Those who shared the high-cost view, especially some American
analysts, argued that a large sum of money has to be spent in
improving the interoperability and facilities of new members,
modernizing new member forces, equipping and training old NATO
allies to ensure their commitment to protect new members from
attack and accommodating new members in NATO headquarters in
Brussels and NATO command facilities elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Department, however, reported its much lower
estimate to the Congress earlier this year, lowering the expansion
cost to between 27 billion and 35 billion dollars between now and
the year of 2009.
</P>
<P>
Those who supported the less-cost projection explained that the
money is better concentrated on enhancing compatibility and
interoperability in command systems, telecommunications and air
defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Poland, which had a similar projection, said that the inclusion
of this central European country into the North Atlantic alliance
would cost no more than 1.26 billion dollars in a 15-year period,
or 84 million dollars per year, an equivalent of 3.3 percent of
the country's 1995 defense budget.
</P>
<P>
Yet one often-overlooked impetus to NATO enlargement is that it
will automatically expand markets for defense industry giants like
Boeing, Raytheon and Lockheed-Martin Marietta.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic that were invited to
join the military alliance last July are reportedly evaluating
such jet fighters as Saab AB's JAS 39 Gripen, Dassault's Mirage,
Lockheed-Martin's F-16 and McDonnel Douglas Corp.'s F-18.
</P>
<P>
One report said orders for aircrafts from those countries in
August could generate 10 billion dollars of business for Western
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
But the three invitees may hope that a new round of
conventional arms control in central and eastern Europe can help
reduce the financial burdens on them and prospective new members.
</P>
<P>
Harry Cohen, chief speaker of today's discussion on economic
affairs at the North Atlantic Assembly annual session, said that
the problem in cost estimation lied in the fact that both analysts
and pundits have bandied about divergent estimates.
</P>
<P>
"A principal source of this confusion is that cost estimates
are assumption driven," said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
"The assumptions include: estimates of the nature and degree of
risk; the requisite degree of assurance the alliance needs to
provide new members; the time frame for achieving this assurance;
the adequacy of current capabilities and procurement policies; the
impact of strategic adjustments undertaken by NATO countries prior
to expansion; and the political and economic acceptability of the
resulting military requirements." he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that new studies would emerge to be less hypothetical
and more rooted in the commitments that are actually being
undertaken as the details of accession negotiations become known.
</P>
<P>
NATO is conducting its own cost study and is expected to
present a report in mid-November in preparation for the
decision-making meeting of NATO defense ministers in December.
</P>
<P>
Large or small, it's not easy to reach a consensus over
enlargement cost in the west, where taxpayers are likely to be
reluctant to support additional military spending in the post-Cold
War era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
