<HEADLINE> Hainan Intensifies Environmental Watch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 11 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan Province
has introduced an environmental protection monitoring program as
part of an effort to intensify local control efforts.
</P>
<P>
An inspection team consisting of deputies to the Provincial
People's Congress, experts and reporters will examine and assess
environmental quality and pollution control efforts of 10 cities
and counties, including Haikou, Sanya and Qionghai.
</P>
<P>
The inspection, which will focus on the protection of forests,
coral reefs and mangrove orchards, is part of local government
efforts to control industrial pollution.
</P>
<P>
The province, home to the country's largest tropical rain
forest and variety of rare animal and plant species, is also a
region with the most abundant tropical resources and biological
diversity in China.
</P>
<P>
It also has the country's largest marine area which is home to
800 species of marine species, or 40 percent of total species
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the island province has maintained
long-term high level environmental quality, pollution problems are
increasing in some areas and some virgin forests and shelterbelts
along the coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
