<HEADLINE> African Churches Urges to Face challenges of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The general assembly of
the All Africa Conference of Churches (AACC) wound-up here Friday
with a call to member churches to rise to the challenges of the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
A resolution adopted at the end of the seventh general
assembly of the AACC urged member churches to renew their
commitment to the political, social and economic transformation
of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The resolution noted that the political commitment will help
use reconciliation mechanisms to prevent, manage and resolve the
wounds and to restore harmony for peaceful co-existence in
African societies.
</P>
<P>
It said that to achieve the goal, strong campaigns are needed
for the cancellation of debt by lobbying and networking with
other agencies. Capacity building programs are also needed, which
will equip and strengthen people, especially children, youth and
women, it added.
</P>
<P>
Embarking on investments that are morally acceptable in order
to increase recurrent revenue to ensure financial stability
should be part of the strategy, the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the question of culture in Africa, it calls for
the appreciation of the African cultural and religious heritage
and the restoration of values that will counter the devastating
and destructive effects of globalization.
</P>
<P>
The assembly elected Professor Kewsi Dickson, a Ghanaian, as
president of AACC to replace the outgoing Desmond Tutu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
