<HEADLINE> Russia, Greece Warn Against Turkey on Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Greece have warned
Turkey with war in case that Turkey attacks Russian or Greek ships
carrying Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air missiles to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Russia's warning was issued by Russian ambassador to Nicosia
Georgi Muradov, who in a televised interview Friday night said his
country would consider a "casus belli" any Turkish attack on
Russian ships carrying the anti-aircraft missiles to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Muradov's statement in Athens, Greek Government
Spokesman Demetris Reppas said that Greece would adopt the same
stand if a Greek ship is attacked by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat told the Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation
Television that his country would honor the contract it signed
with Cyprus for the sale of S-300 missile systems to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said the missiles would come to Cyprus unless there was an
agreement on the island's complete demilitarization between the
two Cypriot communities or progress was reached in the Cyprus
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Muradov's statements were welcomed today by some local
newspapers. Greek daily Alithia described Muradov's statement as
a "political leverage."
</P>
<P>
Another daily newspaper Phileleptheros said that the Russian
stand could not be ignored as this affects developments in the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government signed a contract with Russian
manufacturers earlier this year for the purchase of S-300
surface-to-air missiles expected to be deployed in Cyprus in
mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reacted strongly to the missile deal, threatening a
preemptive strike to prevent the missiles' deployment in Cyprus,
fearing that the military balance in the area would change.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Turkish authorities searched some ships
travelling through the Bosporus Straits, suspecting they carry
components of the Russian missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained 35,000 troops in northern part of the
island, which was unilaterally declared by Turkish Cypriots as
a breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
