<HEADLINE> ASEAN Secretary-General Calls for More Efforts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Secretary-General
Ajit Singh today called for more intensive efforts to prevent
haze, which has affected most ASEAN countries over the past two
months, from getting worse.
</P>
<P>
This matter was on the ASEAN agenda for a considerable time and
a program to this effect which included a decision to seek outside
help was made two years ago when the grouping's environment
ministers met in Kuala Lumpur, Ajit Singh told newsmen in Petaling
Jaya near here today after a briefing on the 29th ASEAN Economic
Ministers (AEM) meeting which is to be held on October 16.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general dismissed allegations that ASEAN was not
united in tackling the haze affecting the region, saying the
magnitude of the problem caught the grouping by surprise.
</P>
<P>
"All (of ASEAN) feel the necessity to act because it is a
serious problem affecting the region...the problem has been
recognized and measures to be taken to address it has been agreed
upon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has sent some 1,200 fire fighters to Indonesia to help
quell raging forest fires that have been blamed for the haze.
</P>
<P>
Ajit said "there was help from others as well" including
technical assistance from Singapore, Canada and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has helped Indonesia by sending satellite photographs
to identify problem areas while Australia made available its
aircraft to be used as "water-bombers", he said.
</P>
<P>
The haze has affected Malaysia, Singapore, Brunei and parts of
the Philippines and Thailand, all members of ASEAN.  
</P>
