<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Major Cost Estimates of NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Now that NATO has invited
Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary to negotiate their
accession to the military bloc, the enlargement cost is for sure
to loom over the coming ratification debates in the parliaments of
NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
Though NATO will not come out with its own estimate of
enlargement cost until mid-November, there were four major
preliminary estimates made by the U.S. Congressional Budget
Office, the independent Rand Corporation, the U.S. administration
and the Polish Euro-Atlantic Association.
</P>
<P>
Following are the cost projections made by the four
institutions:
</P>
<P>
1. In March 1996, the U.S. Congressional Budget Office (CBO)
disclosed the first extensive study on NATO enlargement cost in a
special report. But because the study projected very high costs
ranging from 60.6 billion to 125 billion U.S. dollars, it has
become the target of sharp criticism ever since.
</P>
<P>
The CBO report, which was based on the assumption that Slovakia
would also be invited to join in the first wave, made a lowest
price tag of 60.6 billion dollars, of which new members would pay
42 billion, the United States 4.8 billion and non-U.S. NATO allies
13.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
2. In late 1996, the Rand Corporation published its cost estimate
in the autumn issue of the journal Survival.
</P>
<P>
The Rand Corp. forecast a cost range from 10 billion to 110 billion
dollars over a period of between 10 and 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The California-based thinktank argued that the new members would
have to bear the greatest share of the cost but they would also derive
the greatest benefit.
</P>
<P>
Should NATO allies station forward deploy troops for defending
central and eastern European countries, the price tag would go up
to 110 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
3. In the spring of 1997, the department of defense under the
Bill Clinton administration presented to the U.S. Congress its
cost estimate that turned out to be significantly lower than the
CBO figure.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration estimated that direct enlargement cost
would average 700 million to 900 million dollars annually for a
total of 9 billion to 12 billion dollars spanning the period of
1997 to 2009.
</P>
<P>
It also came out with an itemized cost-sharing scenario that
breaks down to 35 percent paid by the new members, 50 percent by
non-U.S. NATO allies and 15 percent by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The total cost for the first wave of enlargement, according to
the U.S. administration estimate, would average 2.1 billion to 2.7
billion dollars per year or a total of 27 billion to 35 billion
dollars from 1997 to 2009.
</P>
<P>
4. The Polish Euro-Atlantic Association greatly reduced the
American estimates by stating in a report on the consequences of
NATO enlargement that for Poland alone, the enlargement would cost
no more than 1.26 billion dollars in a 15-year period.
</P>
<P>
The figure breaks down to 84 million dollars a year or 3.3
percent of the 1995 Polish defense budget.
</P>
<P>
The Polish estimate was based on the assumption that the money
for enlargement would be spent on such interoperability priorities
as command systems, telecommunications, air defense systems and
integrated air control as well as modernization of airfields.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month at the annual informal meeting of NATO
defense ministers at Maastricht, the Netherlands, NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana said that the enlargement cost
should not be magnified.
</P>
<P>
"The cost will be perfectly manageable," said the NATO chief at
the Maastricht meeting which highlighted the enlargement cost
together with the issue of the SFOR's future in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO experts are now investigating in the three invitee
countries and they are expected to report their cost estimate to
NATO authorities in mid-November in the run-up to the December
decision-making meeting of defense ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
