<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stresses Copper and Aluminium Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China will expand its
nonferrous metals industry, especially oxidized copper and refined
aluminium, with a projected total investment between 1996-2000
expected to hit 45 billion yuan, according to an official of the
State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Chen Dajiang, director of the commission's Nonferrous Metals
Section, said Friday that the country's output of ten major
nonferrous metals in 1996 hit 5.2 million tons, ranking second in
the world next to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Four of China's 1,400 aluminium and copper plants only have a
combined annual production capacity of more than 50,000 tons each,
with most small plants currently operating at a loss.
</P>
<P>
The sector will exert greater efforts to avoid redundant
construction in the coming years, and will upgrade its technology
by raising funds from different channels in order to enhance
market competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The country will need some five million tons of ten major
nonferrous metals by the end of the century, including 1.3 million
tons of copper and 2.3 million tons of aluminium, according to
Chen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
