<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Promises To Reach Grain Self-Sufficiency in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region
promises to yield over one million tons of grain by the year 2000
so as to become self-sufficient in grain.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at various levels in Tibet will invest five
million yuan (about 603,000 US dollars) each year in grain
production, while local people will contribute labor and money
worth five million yuan, too.
</P>
<P>
That one-yuan input should yield one kilogram of grain is the
goal of the newly mapped out project of grain
self-sufficiency. The project will be first carried out in three
cities and prefectures including Lhasa and Xigaze, where there are
greater potentials and better agro-conditions than other areas in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The three areas are expected to produce 30,000-40,000 tons more
of grain annually at the end of this century. The grain
self-sufficiency project will require them to build irrigation
works, enlarge irrigated lands and improve agro-production
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The three areas will also have surplus grains to sell to other
areas in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The year 1996 is Tibet's ninth harvest year. The total grain
production of Tibet reached 770,000 tons. But it still needs
100,000 tons more in order to guarantee 400 kilograms of grain per
person a year. According to the Tibetan agricultural department,
so far 43 out of the region's 75 counties have not reached the
400-kilogram-grain line. Usually it is the central government that
fills the gap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
