<HEADLINE> Perkins Misses Out on Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion and triple
world record holder Kieren Perkins failed to win a berth in the
world swimming championships as he lost his last chance in the
Australian trials on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Perkins, who holds the freestyle world records over 400-, 800-,
1,500-meters, came third in 1,500 meters, clocking 22 seconds
behind winner Grant Hacket.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Hackett won his third title at the trials when
he broke away from Atlanta Olympic silver medalist Daniel Kowalski
to win the 1,500 meters in 15 minutes 01.46 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Kowalski timed 15:08.05 for second place, also qualifying for
the championships. Perkins timed 15:23.45.
</P>
<P>
Perkins said he would return to training in preparation for
next April's trials for the Kuala Lumpur Commonwealth Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
"I want to stay in the sport because it's what I love," he
said. 
</P>
