<HEADLINE> 74 Confirmed Dead in Argentine Plane Crash in Uruguay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 11 (Xinhua) -- All 74 people on board an
Argentine DC-9 that crashed in western Uruguay died in the
accident, an Argentine air force statement said today.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the twin-engine airliner, which crashed late
Friday in a swampy, hilly area outside the Uruguayan border town
of Fray Bentos, is spread over a vast area of rough terrain, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine domestic airliner, carrying 69 passengers and
five crew members, crashed at 11 p.m. local time when trying to
avoid a heavy storm.
</P>
<P>
The DC-9 of the Austral airlines was en route from Posada in
northeast Argentina to Buenos Aires when it disappeared from the
radar screen of air controllers at the Buenos Aires airport.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams from both Uruguay and Argentina rushed to the
crash site about 450 kilometers north of Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the crash is under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
