<HEADLINE> West African Foreign Ministers Meet on Sierra </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 11 (Xinhua) --Five foreign ministers from five
west African states met Friday in Nigerian capital Abuja to
discuss the situation in Sierra Leone, after the U.N. has imposed
sanctions on its military government.
</P>
<P>
A committee of five comprising Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea, Liberia
and Cote d'Ivoire has been set up by the Economic Community of
the West African States (ECOWAS) to deal with the S. Leonean problem
after the country's former president Ahmed Kabbah was overthrown in
a coup last May.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the committee commended the U.N. for its
October 8 resolution that approves oil, arms and other sanctions
against Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Chief Tom Ikimi said the resolution
is in "close alignment" with the decision of the ECOWAS summit of
heads of state in Abuja over a month ago.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi urged the military government led by Major Paul Johnny
Kromah to leave for the re-instatement of elected President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah who was overthrown during the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Ghanian Foreign Minister Victor Gbeho called for an
examination of the U.N. resolution to harmonize it with that the
ECOWAS, "even though it supports our action on Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS's Acting Executive Secretary, Muhammadou Ohoumoudou,
expressed the hope for an earlier end to the crisis in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
"Now that we have received endorsement of the international
community on what we are doing in Sierra Leone, let's see how
quickly we can resolve the issue," said Ohoumoudou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
