<HEADLINE> Macao Budget for 1998 Expected to Rise 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 budget of the Macao
government, which is being drafted, is expected to increase five
percent over this year, a report said.
</P>
<P>
The local daily newspaper Correio Sino-Macaense today quoted
government sources as saying that the government expected
budgetary expenditure for 1998, which excludes some departments
responsible for their own expenditures, will increase five percent
over this year.
</P>
<P>
That would translate to about 10.4 billion patacas (about
1.316 billion US dollars) if calculated from this year's final
budget of 9.914 billion patacas (about 1.255 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government is now drafting the new budget and its policy
address for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure initially announced for 1997 was 9.912 billion
patacas (about 1.255 billion US dollars), and then over two
million patacas (about 253,000 US dollars) were added, according
to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The government spent more than 7.9 billion patacas (about one
billion US dollars) in 1993, and the figure surged to 9.2 billion
patacas (about 1.16 billion US dollars) in 1994, up 16.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure rise then slowed down at a one-digit rate up
until 1997, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of government expenditure has been a heated topic
among local media. Some leading Chinese newspapers carried
editorials urging the government to spend less and save some money
for the future Macao Special Administrative Region, which will be
established in December 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's New Charter Comes into Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's new constitution has
come into force tonight after King Bhumibol Adulyadej signed it,
written on a traditional scroll, this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, National Assembly
President Wan Muhamad Nor Matha, Senate Speaker Meechai Ruchupan,
Constitution Drafting Assembly Chairman Uthai Pimchaichon and
opposition leader Chuan Leekpai attended the signing ceremony held
at the palace.
</P>
<P>
Parliament President Wan Muhamad Nor Matha contersigned the
charter after it was inked by the king.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution took effect immediately after it is
published in the Royal Gazette after the king's signature.
</P>
<P>
The complicated and controversial constitution has been praised
by the general public as the means to reduce, if not wipe out
completely, money politics, which has characterized Thai political
life for decades.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a great number of people, politicians in particular,
find many clauses in it inappropriate to Thailand, a country ruled
through constitutional monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Under the new constitution, approved by the parliament on
October 27 with an overwhelming majority, the House of
Representatives becomes the Upper House, while the Senate becomes
the Lower House: senators, like MPs, will be elected, instead of
through appointment.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will have only 36 members, instead of the current
49.
</P>
<P>
Members of the House of Representatives, once become cabinet
members, i.e., prime minister, ministers or deputy ministers, will
lose their MP status.
</P>
<P>
After the new constitution came into force, three organic laws
governing general elections will be drafted. After their passage,
new general elections will be held in accordance with the new
constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
