<HEADLINE> Portugal to Help Mozambique Manage Trans-Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Portugal will help Mozambique
manage trans-border rivers in accordance with an agreement
signed between Portuguese and Mozambican governments here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement covers four water conservancy and irrigation
projects with a budget of 1.65 million U.S. Dollars in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Robert White, Public Engineering and Housing Minister of
Mozambique and Richardo Magalhaes, Portuguese State Secretary of
Natural Resources, signed the agreement on behalf of their
respective governments.
</P>
<P>
White said after the signing of the agreement that his
government wishes the cooperation will extends to the maintenance
of the basic infrastructures projects as rural and urban water
supply.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, financed by the two governments and the
international community, must be carried out seriously, White
said.
</P>
<P>
Magalhaes said that his government would, apart from its aid
in managing the trans-border rivers, consider to help Mozambique
in securing safety of its dams and in the development of the
Nampula River areas in northern Mozambique, the survey of the
delta areas of Zambeze River in Central Mozambique and the
training of the Mozambican technicians.
</P>
<P>
He said that Portugal and Mozambique, both countries located
at ends of trans-border rivers, face complicated management
problems.
</P>
<P>
Magalhaes arrived here Wednesday for a two-day visit to
Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
