<HEADLINE> HK Hunts for Qualified English Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is to initiate a
worldwide hunt for well-trained native English-speaking teachers
in two months to boost proficiency in the language among local
students.
</P>
<P>
Today's Hong Kong Standard reported that the Education
Department of the Special Administrative Region is liaising with
employment agencies to launch a worldwide recruitment exercise for
700 English-language teachers.
</P>
<P>
Under the new Native-speaking English Teachers Scheme announced
by Chief Executive Tung Chee-Hwa, there will be 700 teachers to
"make an immediate impact on improving English language standard"
in secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
This is in addition to the existing scheme allowing two native
English speaking teachers in each school. The new scheme will cost
254 million HK dollars (32.56 million US dollars) in 1998-99 and
570 million HK dollars (73.08 million US dollars) in 2001-2002.
