<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Summit Adopts 21st Century Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STRASBOURG, France, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Council of
Europe today adopted a declaration and a plan of action for the
21st century at the end of a two-day summit meeting in this French
city.
</P>
<P>
In the two documents, European leaders pledged a ban on
advancing the cloning technology to create a human being identical
to another human being, whether living or dead.
</P>
<P>
They promised to improve human rights among the Council's 40
member states through the European Court of Human Rights, which
will have enhanced powers and streamlined procedures from November
1998 to become the only body monitoring the implementation of the
European Human Rights Convention.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also asked the Council to seek partnerships to
develop new information technologies to ensure cultural diversity
and improve education on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Under the declaration, all member states will boost cooperation
and confidence-building measures to build upon the European
convention guaranteeing ethnic minorities' political, cultural and
religious rights.
</P>
<P>
The summit agreed to carry out the European Social Charter,
strengthen the protection of the weakest members of society,
guarantee the rights of legal immigrants and improve quality of
life in industrialized urban areas while working together to
improve legal protection of women and children against violence
and sexual exploitation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the leaders called for new measures to enhance
cooperation against terrorism, and agreed to seek guidelines for
joint responses to corruption, organized crime, money laudering
and drug trafficking on a continent-wide scale by the end of the
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, South Korea Draw 1-1 in World Cup Tie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMATY, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan held South Korea to a
1-1 draw in the Asian World Cup soccer qualifying tournament here
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Choi Yong-Soo put South Korea in lead 10 minutes into play and
Yevtiev hit the equalizer at the 51st minute.
</P>
<P>
South Korea now tops the five-team Group B with 13 points from
four wins and one draw.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates finished second with seven points from
four games. Japan placed third with five points, followed by
Kazakhstan in three and Uzbekistan in one.
</P>
<P>
The group winner goes to the French finals and runner-up has to
fight with its counterpart in Group A for a berth. Loser in the
clash of the runner-ups will vie for the remaining spot with
Australia in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
