<HEADLINE> Abacha Still Not Decides Whether to Succeed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Sani Abacha said on Friday that he has not yet decided whether or
not to contest the 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
"It is something that one has to think about and articulate,"
Abacha told a 20-man delegation of traditional rulers from
Nigeria's nine eastern states, who are pressuring on him to
succeed himself.
</P>
<P>
"I have heard your message, it's a very difficult one. when
you are talking, I couldn't talk. I was just listening, I was
telling my colleagues that I did not expect this sort of thing,
so this is not for me to answer. It's a difficult message,"
Abacha said, quoted by This Day newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
The head of state pointed out that quite "a number of us here
have made supreme sacrifice for the sake of this nation. It is
God that keeps Nigerians together".
</P>
<P>
The issue whether or not Abacha should become a civial
president at the end of the three-year transition to civil rule
program next October has been much talked about in and out of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the head of state openly commented on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
Last February, Abacha said in an interview with the Washington
Times it would be decided by his constituency if he should
participate in the forthcoming presidential election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
