<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Percent of Drugs Sold in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 11 (Xinhua) -- An alarming 10 percent of
pharmaceuticals on pharmacy shelves in South Africa may be
counterfeit, the today's Star newspaper quoted the managing
director of the Pharmaceuticals Manufactures' Association (PMA)
as saying.
</P>
<P>
A counterfeit drug could be a pill or medicine with no active
ingredient and often include talcum powder or sand. Non-sterile
water was sometimes used in drips and is fatal when injected, PMA
Managing Director Mirryena Deeb said.
</P>
<P>
"You get your more sophisticated counterfeiters, who put a
little bit of active ingredient into it, so it will pass a
superficial chemical test," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said counterfeit pharmaceuticals have been uncovered but
she refused to mention the brands for fear of scare in the
market.
</P>
<P>
The report also said state staff are stealing pharmaceuticals
from hospitals and state warehouses, doctors and pharmacists are
selling them.
</P>
<P>
The PMA official warned that criminals repackage toxic drugs
with false expiry dates and some of these available on streets
can kill.
</P>
<P>
In a major hospital in Gauteng province, more than half of the
drugs are believed to be stolen, some of them resold into the
private sector, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
State organizations are the major source of illicit
pharmaceuticals, West Rand South African Narcotics Bureau chief
Lobo das Neves said.
</P>
<P>
Even crime syndicates have infiltrated into the field.
Medicines Control Council (MCC) leader Johan Koch said syndicate
leaders bribe staff of state hospitals,institutions and
pharmacies, and some dispensing doctors are among the buyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
