<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Disappointed over Australia's Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today expressed his disappointment over an
allegation by Australia that his government rejected a bid by
Australia's Transfield Defense Systems company for a defense
contract to hit back at the Australian government.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was commenting on news reports quoting Australian
Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer as blaming Australian former
Prime Minister Paul Keating's rift with his Malaysian counterpart
for the loss of the 5.6 billion ringgit (about 1.83 billion U.S.
dollars) contract to build 27 warships for the Royal Malaysian
Navy.
</P>
<P>
Keating caused a major political row between Malaysia and
Australia in 1993 by describing Mahathir as recalcitrant for not
attending the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) meeting in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
"We feel sad by such an allegation, " Mahathir was quoted by
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama as telling reporters
after a function in the northeastern states of Terengganu today.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that there was never such an intention (to hit
back) and the question of revenge did not arise and such an
allegation should not have been made.
</P>
<P>
"To say that we did not offer (the contract) to Australia to
hit back is not very nice. Surely we are not expected to offer
everything to Australia," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that Malaysia received proposals from various
parties which were all capable and it was up to the government to
make its choice.
</P>
<P>
Shortlisted for the contract were four companies -- Transfield,
Danish Naval Group, Vosper Thornycraft and the German Naval Group,
a consortium of four German companies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The contract was reported to have been offered to a German
consortium, Bernama said. but according to Mahathir, he had not
yet received any information on the contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
