<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Special Envoy for Cyprus to Visit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Special Envoy for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke will pay his first visit to Turkey since his
appointment to mediate the protracted Cyprus problem, Foreign
Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke's visit is aimed at exchanging views with Turkish
leaders over the Cyprus peace talks, local newspaper Daily News
today quoted high-ranking officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. special envoy is coming in the next few days without a
specified agenda and will not carry any official message from
Washington, said the sources who are not identified in the report.
</P>
<P>
They said that Ankara will use this opportunity to express its
position and to learn Washington's views over the reconciliation
process on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, a small island state in the eastern Mediterranean, has
been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north and Greek
Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus", which is recognized only by
Turkey, aggravating confrontation between the two rival
communities.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is expected to meet Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem and other Turkish officials in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
After his contacts in Ankara, Holbrooke will fly to Nicosia to
meet Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash. Then he will visit Athens where he will hold
talks with Greek leaders.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash held two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct
talks in the United States and Switzerland in July and August, but
no agreement was achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
