<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Speed up phone Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will spend at least 10
billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 800 million U.S. Dollars) within
the next five years in installing new telephone lines throughout
the country in a move to reduce the long-standing waiting list.
</P>
<P>
Addressing to a three-day conference of the Zimbabwe Institute
of Public Finance and Accountancy yesterday, Zimbabwe's Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) planing director Tororiro
Chaza said the corporation intends to use a mixture of internally
sourced funds and loans.
</P>
<P>
Chaza stressed the need to extend telephone services to both
urban and outlying areas. He noted that in most successful
economies, an efficient telecommunication service has been
regarded as a factor of production.
</P>
<P>
Economic commentators have also cited Zimbabwe's poor
telecommunication system as one of the major constraints
restricting potential foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
About 433,000 lines can be installed in the five-year term.
This will improve teledensity (the number of telephones per 100
people) from the current 1.8 to 3.06.
</P>
<P>
"But the forecast has to be revised upwards as there are signs
of higher demand due to suppressed demand," said Chaza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
