<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Iran to Curb Border Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Iran have agreed
to make joint efforts to identify and apprehend criminals
operating along their common border.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken at a two-day conference of border
officials from Pakistan and Iran, which ended on Friday at Nushki,
about 140 kilometers west of Quetta, capital of Baluchistan
province, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the two countries decided to set up joint
patrol teams along the common border to check anti-social
elements.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also decided to take strict measures to
control the movement of Afghan refugees and Bengali nationals near
Pak-Iran border.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the next meeting of its kind will be held
early December at Zahidan, Iran.  
</P>
