<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Asks Mombasa to Serve the Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has urged Kenya's port
of Mombasa to be prepared for the rise of commercial transport,
The Monitor reported today.
</P>
<P>
John Nasasira, Ugandan Minister of Works, Transport and
Communication, said Uganda plans to build roads and a railway
line linking Uganda and Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of normalizing situation both in Congo and
north-western Uganda, commerce, construction and transport in the
north-western Uganda are booming, according to a recent report
reaching here. The north-western Ugandan region has erected roads
linking eastern Congo and southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar of the Kenya Port Authority (KPA) on
October 9, the minister suggested Mombasa should serve the whole
region.
</P>
<P>
I.J. Mwangola, the managing director of KPA, said on the
occasion that Port Mombasa now put into use only 42 percents of
its transport capacity. He promised to improve its service.
</P>
<P>
With the looming business opportunities in the region, two
regional ports -- Mombasa of Kenya and Dar-es-Salaam of Tanzania,
are competing in local transport market. Both ports established
offices in kampala recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
