<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Offshore Oil Industry Sets Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- (Editor's Notes: The 15th World
Petroleum Congress is to open in Beijing on October 12. Xinhua
News Agency is expected to release a series of backgrounders to
outline the development of China's oil industry.)
</P>
<P>
China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC), China's second
largest oil developer, plans to keep its crude oil production at
14 million tons a year through to the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Also on its planning agenda is to secure two million tons of
crude oil from its overseas ventures.
</P>
<P>
The natural gas production capacity is planned to reach 8.5-10
billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
To this end, CNOOC is to verify 80 million tons of oil in place
and 60 billion cubic meters of natural gas. CNOOC also plans to
bring five oilfields on-stream.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC early last year inaugurated production with US-based
Amoco at Liuhua 11-1, China's largest offshore oilfield whose peak
production capacity is projected at 2.5 million tons annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tower of Torch Erected out of Dilemma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- From within the Shanghai
"Barrel" Complex, a sculptural tower of torch was erected up
outside, beckoning in the Eighth National Games in China's most
populous city.
</P>
<P>
The tower of torch, with a historical note at the height of
19.97 meters, was originally supposed to be created within the
bounds of the complex when the designers drew the blueprint for
the newly-built 80,000-capacity complex.
</P>
<P>
Yet, all the constructors looked at each other aghast in April
as to wherein the tower to sit when the caps of fibre glass were
to be tightened to shadow all the seats within the kidney-like
complex.
</P>
<P>
All were plunged into a dilemma as the original blueprint was
casted into the rubbish bin since a mobile tower, supposed to be
set up in the field, is surely unable to set the holy flames
flaring in the wind at the limited height of four meters.
</P>
<P>
To put it in the stands will occupy some 300 seats for ever, a
big sacrifice for the complex. Besides, the glittering flame
poses a permanent risk to the caps of fibre glass, necessitating
an additional fire-proof shelve.
</P>
<P>
To go from bad to worse, the supply of gas also was a nagging
problem, and became virtually impossible since the pipe has to be
connected in the depth of 10 meters underground as the structure
of the complex was already cemented firmly.
</P>
<P>
Thus, designers racked their brains for a pool of suggestions,
including an air-lifting of the tower by helicopter to highlight
the festive atmosphere, but the whimsy-whamsy was rejected in the
bud as any helicopter is doomed to be pulled down to the floor
by the tower.
</P>
<P>
Months of efforts betrayed everyone before Gong Xueping, vice
mayor of Shanghai finalized the decision on May 16 to shift the
tower from within.
</P>
<P>
All in a hurry, the constructers, pipe workers and designers
combined their witts and efforts to set up the tower in three
months with two gas pipes, two water pipes, four lighters and 92
burners.
</P>
<P>
With a huge torch standing atop, the tower was erected upon a
platform decorated with sculptures of athletes, depicting the
harmonious marriage between arts and sports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
