<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Spends More on Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China spent over 226 billion
yuan (more than 27 billion US dollars) on education in 1996, 20.47
percent more than it did the previous year, according to a latest
statistics report.
</P>
<P>
Of the total expenditure for eduction, 167.17 billion yuan
(about 20.14 billion US dollars) came from state revenue in 1996,
representing an 18.43 percent over 1995. It accounted for 2.44
percent of China's gross domestic product and 16.28 percent of its
budget in 1996, up 0.03 percentage points and 0.23 percentage
points over the previous year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The statistics report also showed that last year central and
local governments' allocations for education increased by 17.85
percent to 121.191 billion yuan (about 14.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report was jointly released by the State Education Commission
(SEC) and the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A SEC official said that the report unveiled that the overall
education input has been increased remarkably, especially when being
calculated on the basis of the average expense for each student.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the growth of local government
allocation to education in a number of provinces and
municipalities has outpaced that of their regular revenue. They
include Beijing, Tianjin municipalities and Jiangsu, Zhejiang,
Jiangxi, Guangdong, Guizhou, Yunnan and Qinghai provinces.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said, regional disparity still exits,
adding that some local governments failed to meet the requirements
of education input set by the Education Law.
</P>
<P>
China began to make public its education expenses once a year
in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF Should Desist From Blackmailing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi said that the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) should desist from blackmailing Kenya in the
disbursement of financial aid.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times today quoted the president as saying Friday at
a Moi Day rally that "it should be understood that when we are
dealing with (economic) reforms, we are thinking first of the
welfare of Kenyans."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the implementation of structural
adjustment programs adversely affected the vulnerable groups in
society, particularly children, women and the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that the recent suspension of a loan package to Kenya
by the two international financial institutions resulted partly
from a delay in restructuring the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of the energy sector require parliamentary
approval, noted the president, adding that "we don't have to
hurry them" and the government was willing to continue
collaborating with the Bretton Woods institutions.
</P>
<P>
The IMF lapsed the second disbursement of its 215 million U.S.
Dollars three-year program offered under the Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility on July 31.
</P>
<P>
Some days ago, Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa
also criticized Structural Adjustment Programs, saying they were
"immoral and deserved condemnation". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
