<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Strikers Urged to Refrain from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Striking farm workers should
desist from violence and destruction of farm property and
commodities of lands and agriculture, Zimbabwean Minister of
Lands and Agriculture Kumbirai Kangai said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, Kangai urged commercial farmers
to speedily reach a mutually satisfactory resolution with their
striking workers to end the current impasse.
</P>
<P>
The government may be forced to intervene if the two
negotiating parties failed to reach an agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
Wage negotiations between the farmers and their workers
reached a deadlock last week for the first time in this country,
resulting in the matter being referred for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
"Let me emphasize that the government would like to see
commercial farmers and their workers reaching a mutually
satisfactory resolution to the current impasse," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
"But we are concerned about the violence and destruction of
farm property and commodities," said Kangai.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the destruction of property is against
the law.
</P>
<P>
Property worth millions of dollars has been destroyed on farms
since the workers' strike started at the end of last month.
</P>
<P>
The government is also aware that there are some criminal
elements who are not farm workers, but they are roaming farming
areas intimidating farmers and workers.
</P>
<P>
Police are all out to look for these criminals and some have
already been arrested.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the farming season has just begun. There are
some crops, particularly the early crops under irrigation, such
as tobacco, whose seeds need to be transplanted.
</P>
<P>
Both farmers and workers should not allow such crops to go any
further under stress, "as that will lead to losses in production.
losses in revenue and therefore losses in future wages," he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to both workers and commercial farmers for greater
initiative and a creative response to the situation now facing
the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
