<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Swimming World Records Expected from National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese swimmers are
orchestrated to win more gold medals instead of setting any world
record in the coming Eighth National Games, a top Chinese swimming
official said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Ming, vice head coach of the Chinese National Swimming
Team, explained that "the gold medals are valued more precious
than any record in the Games by all the participating delegations
as each of them carries out a stereotyped gold-oriented
blueprint."
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Le Jingyi "is expected only to retain her
national title, a precious gold already accounted by the Shanghai
delegation," said Zhou, who also serves as head coach of the
Shanghai swimming squad.
</P>
<P>
Under such a circumstance, no world record is expected to be
set up in the swimming pool as more attention will be swifted to
winning the gold medals, even in miserable timings, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the competitions will still be tough enough as the games
will also serves as a qualifying tournament for the World Swimming
Championships to be held in Perth in January, the coach said.
</P>
<P>
Such a tight schedule may hinder the Chinese swimmers in the
World Championships, and both coaches and the athletes have to
sacrifice the records for the gold medals at home, Zhou Ming
explained.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, the Chinese swimmers failed to create any world
record in the Seventh National Games in Beijing, but they made big
splashes in Rome in the succeeding World Championships by winning
a total of 12 gold medals, some of them in world records. Endtiem
nnnn
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
