<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Decide on Olympic Bid After National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China will decide whether to
launch another bid to host the Olympic Games after the Eighth
National Games and Shanghai might step in as the second Chinese
city to submit such an application, top Chinese officials said
here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu, minister of the State Physical Culture and Sports
Commission (SPCSC), stressed China's attitude that the country
"has yet to seriously ponder upon the issue."
</P>
<P>
"We will make the final decision whether or not to launch
another bidding campaign after the National Games," he said at the
news conference prior to the opening of the Eighth National Games.
</P>
<P>
Beijing lost to Sydney in the most intense-ever bidding race
for the 2000 Olympic Games in 1993 due to "non-sport factors," as
Wu put it.
</P>
<P>
While Beijing was expected to submit its candidancy once China
decides to bid anew, Shanghai, China's most populous and largest
city, might also make a try as it is striving to become the
world's financial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
"The bidding campaign is a matter between contries. It's up to
the SPCSC to make the decision and we have no say upon it," said
Shanghai vice mayor Gong Xueping who also serves as vice chairman
of the Games' Organizing Committee.
</P>
<P>
But Gong pointed out that if SPCSC eventually favors another
bid and chooses Shanghai as the bidding candidate, Shanghai will
not let the chance slip off its hands.
</P>
<P>
"Then we will try our best to bring the Olympics home," Gong
said. "Right now, the priority should go to the National Games."
</P>
<P>
The Eighth National Games, the last major sports meet of China
in the centrury, will ring up its curtain on Sunday with
historical colors.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, that returned to China on July 1 after 156 years
under British rule, will make its debut in the comprehensive
sports meet under the name of "Hong Kong, China."
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, which was reported to exploit Hong Kong experiences
for its economic development, will take the opportunity to further
relations with Hong Kong, tagged as the "Pearl of Oriental."
</P>
<P>
"The two sides have forged very close ties in sports. Hong
Kong's return to the motherland provides precious favorable
conditions for our further cooperation," Gong said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the two metropolitans have had an annual inter-port
soccer tournament since 1987. The recent match was held last
month, with Shanghai winning as the host.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the two sides will establish a soccer league featuring
all the top clubs," Gong said.
</P>
<P>
Gong also said that Shanghai has a lot to learn from Hong Kong
in horse racing. "We hope Hong Kong could give us a hand in the
horse racing."
</P>
<P>
Wu uttered his support for the inter-port cooperation in sports
beteen Hong Kong and Shanghai, but reminded that it must go in
accordance with the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
