<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deforestation in Bangladesh Threatens Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The existence of wild animals and
birds in Bangladesh has been threatened due to massive
deforestation and indiscriminate cutting of trees in four
districts of this South Asian country, local press reports said
here today.
</P>
<P>
About 10 species of wild animals have already vanished from the
districts, while 10 more species are on the verge of extinction,
according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Illegal hunting, cruelty to wildlife, rapid settlement of human
beings and deforestation have led to this situation, the reports
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The four districts were rich in wildlife like porcupine, civet,
rabbit, fox, wild cat, mongoose, green frogs, tortoise, oyster,
squirrel and different kinds of birds two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has 105 species of mammals, 567 of birds and 129 of
reptiles which constitute rich wildlife resources of the country,
some experts noted, suggesting establishment of wildlife
sanctuaries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, wild birds have started migrating to safer
sanctuaries because law violators are seen shooting birds and
animals frequently, and some of them even mix poison with food to
catch animals, some experts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rice Yield Edges Up in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's rice yield is
estimated to edge up to 5.35 million metric tons this year, a 0.5
percent rise over the previous year's 5.32 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry said in a
report that the projected harvest, the highest in six years, is
9.9 percent more than the ministry's target for this year.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural ministry attributed the harvest to favorable
weather and the efforts by the government and farmers to secure
more rice-cultivating areas and develop high-quality paddies.
</P>
