<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's Tin, Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of tin
and rubber closed the week all lower.
</P>
<P>
This week, a strong recovery of the Malaysian Ringgit, which
closed at 3.0610/10 to the U.S. dollar from 3.3230/50 a week ago,
hit the tin and rubber markets.
</P>
<P>
The tin price on the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), which
touched an eight-year high last week when it closed at 20.22
Ringgit per kg due to the weakened Ringgit, closed this week
sharply lower by 3.65 Ringgit to 16.57 Ringgit per kg.
</P>
<P>
Turnover this week fell to 385 tons from 470 tons last week.
There were more offerors instead of bidders for tin as many buyers
shied away from the market due to the strengthening of the Ringgit
coupled with the downtrend on the LME that dampened market
sentiment further.
</P>
<P>
Trading this week was dominated mostly by buyers from Europe
and locals while Japanese buyers stayed away.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market this week, the strengthening of
the Ringgit sparked some selling interest and kept most rubber
traders on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
November RSS One and SMR 20 each eased by nine sen to close at
281.50 sen (about 92 U.S. cents) per kg and 279.50 sen (about 91
U.S. cents) per kg respectively.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for October 9 stood at 208.42
Malaysia/Singapore cents per kg against 212.23 cents on October 2.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average this week stood at 212.59 cents per
kg against 206.07 cents per kg last week.
</P>
<P>
The performance of the local rubber market next week will
depend on the Ringgit's trend against the U.S. dollar, a dealer
said.
</P>
<P>
The strengthening of the Ringgit this week sparked some selling
interest and kept most rubber traders on the sidelines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
