<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Build Houses for Street Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is to
establish committees in Nairobi and other cities to provide homes
for street children, the Kenya Times today quoted President
Daniel arap Moi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moi was speaking Friday at a garden party held here at the State
House in Nairobi for some 2,000 street children in celebration of
this year's Moi Day.
</P>
<P>
He said that the committee to be set up in Nairobi would build
homes for street children in the capital city and provide them
with an opportunity to learn useful skills.
</P>
<P>
Similar committees will also be established in other parts of
the East African country with the financial support of the Moi
Children Fund, the president announced.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the street children of today would be adults in
the future, adding that there was need to mould them into
dependable children.
</P>
<P>
On the Moi Day, the president visited the Thomas Barnado House
and Mama Ngina Kenyatta Children's homes, and donated foodstuffs
like biscuits, rice, sugar, bread and milk to them.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by Human Rights Watch earlier
this year, Kenya has more than 40,000 street children, 25,000 of
whom are concentrated on Nairobi streets.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in addition to the hazards of living on
the streets, these children who live outside the protection of
responsible adults face harassment and abuse from the police.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government announced in June this year that five
rescue centers would be set up in urban areas for practical
support of street children.
</P>
<P>
At a Christmas party last year at the State House, President
Moi announced that he had set up a Moi Children
Fund to help raise money and establish homes for the children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
