<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Has Large Percentage of Mental Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has a fairly large
percentage of patients with various types of mental disorders,
said a signed article carried by the just-published weekend
magazine Independent here today.
</P>
<P>
There are about 8.40 million mental patients in Bangladesh at
present, accounting for about 7 percent of the total population
(120 million), according to an official estimate.
</P>
<P>
Of the above-mentioned figure, 1.20 million fall in the
categories of serious mental disorders and 7.20 million in other
less-serious categories, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
However, there are 675 hospital beds for mental patients in the
country, of which 560 are in government hospitals and 115 in
private hospitals, the article quoted the official statistics as
stating.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly 70 percent of the mental patients belonging to urban
background are women," Dr. Anwara Begum, director cum professor of
the Institute of Mental Health, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Various stress factors contribute to the deterioration of a
person's mental state over a certain period of time, the professor
said, adding that urban women from upper-middle and middle classes
face many conflicting situations every day, and the most stressful
of these are interpersonal conflict between husband and wife. This
is the major cause of mental problem among urban women.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Calls for Being Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has stressed the need to restore Tanzania's
respect by eliminating government dependence on donor support
while reducing the overdependence of the people on the
government.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa made the appeal while opening the National Convention on
Development "Vision 2025" Friday in Arusha, according to a news
dispatch from the northern Tanzanian town.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants attending the two-day symposium that
the long-term vision should focus on boosting productivity in
industries, agriculture and mining for a dynamic economy and
stable state to be attained.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that the government wants the people to stop
thinking that the government should single-handedly bring about
national development, adding the new vision entails increased
public participation in national activities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the governmental dependence on external aid has
reached a point whereby even salaries and transport have to be
paid through donor funds, asking, "What sort of independence is
that? What is our integrity as a state?"
</P>
<P>
He noted that in general, dependence has affected Tanzanians
to the extent that individuals wait for the government even for
things that they can do on their own such as building a school
toilet or providing school desks.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that today Tanzania proudly enjoys national unity,
social cohesion, peace and stability, adding the challenge is to
enable Tanzanians realize their full potential, develop
self-confidence and mobilize resources towards the betterment of
the tanzanian society.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the long-term strategy should incorporate
science and technology as well as a sense of commitment among the
people to bring about revolutionary changes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
