<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Revamps Management of Public Sector Undertakings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 11 (Xinhua) -- With the view to giving
financial and operational autonomy for profit-making public sector
undertakings (PSU), the Indian government has issued a set of
guidelines for restructuring PSU boards by broad-basing them and
streamlining their decision-making process, The Hindustan Times
said today.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines, which were issued here late on Friday, stated
that small boards should be broad-based by inducting at least
three non-official part-time directors. It should also be ensured
that the number of the non-official part-time directors increase
to one-third of the total strength of the board at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
While announcing delegation of decision-making for PSUs
earlier, the government had allowed some PSU boards to incur
capital expenditure on new projects, modernization and purchase of
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of power would be subject to several conditions
and guidelines. The expenditure proposals have to be presented to
the board of directors in writing and reasonably well in advance,
with an analysis of relevant factors and quantification of the
anticipated results and benefits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Share prices rebounded on
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) market this week with a
mid-week spurt.
</P>
<P>
The Composite Index, which tracks 100 quality stocks, soared
36.72 points or 4.60 percent to close the week at 834.01 after
moving between a low of 791.02 and a high of 845.56 during the
week.
</P>
<P>
The all main board share Emas Index closed at 234.02, up 9.13
points or 4.05 percent from last week.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial Index rose 63.82 points or 3.88 percent to
1,704.81 and the Second Board Index surged 29.27 points or 7.29
percent to 430.32.
</P>
<P>
The rebound on the KLSE went side by side with the recovery of
the local foreign exchange market with Malaysia's Ringgit traded
at 3.0610/10 to the U.S. dollar at the week's close from 3.3230/50
a week ago.
</P>
<P>
During the week under review, one counter -- Nissan IOI -- made
a good debut on the Second Board, opening on Thursday at 5.90
Ringgit and closing the week at 5.45 Ringgit against its initial
public offering price at 3.90 Ringgit.
</P>
<P>
This week, the main board's ready turnover expanded to
1,149.232 million shares worth 5.1552 billion Ringgit (about
1.6847 billion U.S. dollars) from 761.785 million shares valued at
3.6696 billion Ringgit (about 1.1992 billion U.S. dollars) last
week.
</P>
<P>
The Second Board turnover this week was 231.670 million shares
worth 2,217.985 million Ringgit (about 724.8317 million U.S.
dollars) from last week's 129.647 million shares valued at
1,105.945 million Ringgit (about 361.4199 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said that the bullish sentiments which
re-emerged on the KLSE this week are expected to be carried
forward to next week when the 1998 Budget which is widely believed
to put the economy on the right track will be announced.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 Budget scheduled to be tabled in Parliament on October
17 is expected to be one that will boost confidence and steer the
economy away from stormy weather, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The bullish forecast for the local unit to bounce back to the
2.80 level to the U.S. dollar would also prompt the stock market
to recover further, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
