<HEADLINE> Italian PM Expects Quick Solution to Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi expressed optimism today that there will be a quick
solution to the current Italian government crisis following the
resignation of his government Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's government resigned after failing to get parliament to
endorse plans to cut the budget deficit in line with relevant
measures to adopt the European currency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro began formal
talks today with the chairmen of the Senate and the Chamber of
Deputies, and may announce the dissolution of the parliament
elected 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the European summit in Strasbourg,
France, Prodi said he did not know what solution the president
will seek, but said, "I can assure you that it will be a quick
solution."
</P>
<P>
Though crises have put the country's plan of swapping lira for
the euro in doubt, it has dampened Prodi's optimism over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the chances for Italy to take part in Europe's
single currency "are based on the results we have achieved.
</P>
<P>
"It takes time to build and it also takes time to destroy," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
