<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export to South Africa Rises Six-fold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's export to South
Africa registered a six-fold increase since 1992-93 when trade
transaction between the two countries began, said the sources from
the Commerce and Industries Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
This South Asian country's export to South Africa rose to 248
million taka (about 5.59 million dollars) in 1996-97 (up to March)
from 46 million taka (about 1.04 million dollars) in 1992-93,
according to the official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Major items Bangladesh exported to South Africa were jute and
jute goods, ceramics, leather and leather goods, knitwear,
pharmaceutical products and electrical bulbs.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, items imported from South Africa during the
period under consideration were chemicals, plastic articles,
machinery and electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh established a mission in South Africa in February
1995 and its commercial wing stated operation in October of the
same year.
</P>
<P>
At the present, there is no bilateral trade agreement between
the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
