<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Optimistic to Find Peaceful Resolution on Chechen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia could eventually find a
peaceful solution to the Chechen issue, Deputy Representative of
the Security Council of the Russian Federation Boris Berezovski
told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
Berezovski spoke after talks between representatives from the
Russian federation and Chechen republic Thursday in Soci, a
Russian coastal city along the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
The Chechen representative agreed to submit the two documents
on the republic's status to Russia's State Duma (the lower house
of parliament) and the Federation Council (the upper house), said
Berezovski.
</P>
<P>
However, the two sides still hold differences, Berezovski
said. The Chechen representative insists on signing a
state-to-state agreement with Russia, while Russia only wants to
sign an agreement between the central and local governments.
</P>
<P>
He said that only the Russian parliament could solve that
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Federation and the Chechen Republic reached an
agreement in August 1996 in Khasavyurt, a city in the North
Caucasus region in Russia's Dagestan Republic, ending the war in
Chechnya, which started in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to postpone the issue of Chechnya's status until
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Berezovski said the reasons for the differences were because
they differed on explanations for the postponement. The Chechen
Republic regarded itself as an independent state since 1991.
</P>
<P>
But the security representative still felt optimistic. He said,
"The most serious crisis" between the two sides had been solved
during the Soci meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0181 </DOCNO>
