<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP's aid to Upgrade Water Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The 21st Century Urban Water
Management in China, a project funded by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), will help launch a national drive
for sustainable urban water management in Chinese cities that face
severe water shortage, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"The 1.1-million-US dollar project will support pilot
activities in Shijiazhuang," Liang Dan said yesterday in
Beijing. Liang is director of China's International Center for
Economic and Technical Exchanges, which will execute the project.
</P>
<P>
"Shijiazhuang is a north China city plagued by a lack of water
resources," Liang added. "The project will determine the most
appropriate reforms at the municipal level regarding water
resource management."
</P>
<P>
Half of China's 666 cities are threatened by water shortages,
according to Nie Meisheng, director of the Science and Technology
Department of Ministry of Construction.
</P>
<P>
The nation's per capita water availability is 2,440 cubic
meters, only a quarter of the world's average, Nie added.
</P>
<P>
Each year, an average of 230 billion yuan (27.7 billion US
dollars) in industrial output value has been affected by water
deficiencies, Nie said.
</P>
<P>
She said the UNDP's aid project is of far-reaching significance
and should help China solve the water-related problems that are a
major stumbling block to China's sustainable economic and social
development in the coming century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges Israeli Employers to Rise Wages for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is urging Israeli
employers to increase wages for Thai workers who were supposed to
get a pay rise five months ago, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Most workers receive a daily wage of 600-630 baht (17.1-18 US
dollars), which is about 100 baht (2.8 dollars) less than that
they should obtain under an agreement made between the two
countries, according to a survey by the Thai embassy in Israel.
</P>
<P>
In May, the Thai Labor and Social Welfare Ministry and Moshav
Movement, an Israeli agency in charge of Thai workers, agreed to
increase the basic wages for Thai workers.
</P>
<P>
But many employers ignored the pay rise agreement, especially
those who employed Thai laborers in flower plantations for export.
</P>
<P>
About 18,000 out of 25,000 Thai laborers in Israel work in
agriculture while the rest are in construction, restaurants and
private residences.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish National Jailed in Thailand for Drugs Offense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A Polish national was Friday
sentenced to two and a half years in prison in Thailand for a
drugs offense, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Court initially sentenced Krabowski Andres
Stanislaff, 41, to five years in jail, but as he pleaded guilty to
the charges, his sentence was commuted by half.
</P>
<P>
Stanislaff was arrested on March 28 this year at the Bangkok
International Airport as he was about to board a flight to the
Netherlands. Customs officers asked for body search and found 6
kilograms of dried marijuana wrapped in plastic and taped around
his waist, legs and shoes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
