<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Grants Amnesty to Army Deserters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Army has
declared an amnesty for all deserters and asked them to return to
duty as soon as possible, Defense Ministry sources said today.
</P>
<P>
In view of the 48th anniversary of the Army, which fell on
Friday, the Army decided to grant an amnesty to all deserters, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty will be effective from October 10 to mid-night
October 24.
</P>
<P>
The deserters may report to the nearest military camp or to a
police station.
</P>
<P>
All those report for duty will not be punished and will be
entitled to their earlier held ranks, pay and allowances soon
after their return.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 have reportedly deserted the army in recent
years. Since 1995, the army has offered amnesty for deserters on
five occasions and over 10,000 deserters have reportedly returned.
</P>
<P>
During the latest amnesty on July 10-26 this year, a total of
4,026 army deserters returned for duty.
</P>
<P>
Sources said most of the deserters escaped their duties because
they were afraid of being sent to the front line to fight with the
guerrilla of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), who have
been fighting for a separate state of their own for 14 years in
the north and east of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
