<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Offshore Oil Producer ahead of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 11 (Xinhua) -- China Offshore Oil Nan Hai East
Corp (CONHE) had pumped out more than 10 million tons of crude oil
by October 3, exceeding the annual target of 9.75 million tons one
quarter ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
CONHE is expected to produce more than 12 million tons of crude
oil by the end of this year, according to today's China
Daily. CONHE has yielded 11.84 million tons of crude oil last
year, accounting for 80 percent of China's offshore oil.
</P>
<P>
This level of oil output is projected to continue into the
next century, said China Daily, adding that the South China Sea
fields will therefore be made China's fourth largest oil
producer. The three others are northeast China's Daqing, east
China's Shengli and northeast China's Liaohe.
</P>
<P>
CONHE is operating eight offshore oilfields, including China's
biggest offshore oilfield Liuhua 11-1, with overseas investors in
eastern areas of the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
In the past 14 years, CONHE has cooperated with 38 foreign oil
firms to explore and develop offshore oilfields in a
106,000-square-kilometer area, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"But we have discovered fewer than 10 percent of the largest
oil reserves in the eastern section of the South China Sea," a
CONHE official was quoted as saying. CONHE expects to receive
foreign financial support to help sustain its oil production level
in the next few years, the official added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
