<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects Good for Thailand's Garment Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 11 (Xinhua) -- Export prospects for the Thai
garment industry are good due to the weaker baht, according to
Chavalit Nimla-Or, president of the Thai Garment Manufacturers'
Association.
</P>
<P>
The value of garment exports for the last four months of the
year could be up by 25 percent over the same period last year in
baht terms and by 10 percent in dollars terms, Chavalit was quoted
today by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The value of outbound shipments of garment as of July 31 was
49.16 billion baht (1.96 billion US dollars), up just 1.27 percent
over the 48.54 billion baht (1.94 billion dollars) recorded in the
first seven months of last year.
</P>
<P>
In major markets such as the United States and Japan, which
account for 74 percent of all garment exports from Thailand,
growth has been much higher at 8.84 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said, however, that sales to two smaller markets, the
Middle East and Eastern Europe, could fall by about 30 percent due
to competition from products made in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that Thailand should adopt both short- and
long-term plans for market development, tailored to each region.
Government assistance in terms of finance and technology upgrading
is still needed.
</P>
<P>
A more competitive garment industry must be in place once the
ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) agreement starts to be implemented in
the next two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
But once the agreement takes effect, Thailand should seize the
chance to sell its products within the region since products from
outside, especially from Italy and Hong Kong, will face import
tariff of up to 30 percent. Products manufactured within ASEAN
will carry tariffs ranging from zero to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Even in the low-end market, Thailand should stress quality and
promote the image that the country produces affordable -- but not
low-quality -- products, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Publishes State Message </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's President
Nursultan Abishevich Nazarbayev here today published an annual
state message that explained the country's basic strategy in the
coming 32 years, Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev announced that his country's long-term development
plans are intended to ensure the country's independence and
sovereignty, to guarantee stable politics, national unity,
economic prosperity in a market economy, to improve living
standards, the health and welfare of the population, and to
further develop the energy industry, particularly petroleum and
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev also pointed out that some of the problems his
country has faced in recent years are a struggle with poverty,
unemployment, the improvement of national unity, improving
conditions for investment and its struggle with corruption.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh constitution requires that the president must
publish a state message to the people annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
