<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gains Bigger Textile Quota From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States has agreed to
import more textile products from Sri Lanka following intense
negotiations between the two sides this week in the U.S., local
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new agreement, Sri Lanka will be able to export an
additional amount of textile products valued at 960 million Rupees
(16.3 million U.S. dollars) to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Sri Lankan Industrial Development Minister
C.V. Gooneratne led a delegation to the U.S. to participate in the
two-day negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The apparel industry, which provides over 300,000 jobs,
recorded a 32 percent growth and earned 71 billion Rupees (1.2
billion dollars) in the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
It is also the leading contributor to the country's foreign
exchange earnings and a vital sector in the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
