<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, October 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton said here today that he is
looking forward to the upcoming visit to the United States of
Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Meeting at the White House with Liu Huaqiu, director of the
Office of Foreign Affairs under the State Council of China,
Clinton said that he will discuss with his Chinese counterpart the
American-Chinese relationship and world situation over the next 30
to 50 years. (Clinton-Jiang's Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada said today that Israel has agreed to stop
using Canadian passports in covert operations.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy told parliament that
he got the assurance from his Israeli counterpart, David
Levy. (Canada-Israel-Passports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French President Jacques Chirac and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin announced today in Strasbourg, France, that they
will hold a summit with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl once a year.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted Chirac as saying that a regular
tripartite summit meeting of France, Germany and Russia will make
up "an important force in Europe and notably a necessary element
for the deepening of peace." (France-Germany-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece today warned Turkey that any attack by Ankara
against a Greek vessel would be regarded as a cause for war.
</P>
<P>
The warning was sent out today by Greek government spokesman
dimitris Reppas when asked to comment on statements by Russia's
ambassador in Cyprus, who said that his country would consider as
a "casus belli" a Turkish strike against any Russian ship
transporting S-300 surface-to-air missiles to Nicosia.
(Greece-Turkey-Missiles)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and Japan ended their annual
review of a 1995 auto trade agreement with the U.S. side
expressing disappointment over the lack of progress for enhancing
exports of U.S.-made cars and parts.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day talks, the U.S. had presented a series of
proposals on ways that Japan could speed efforts to remove
barriers to sales of both cars and auto parts, said Wendy Cutler,
assistant U.S. Trade Representative who led the U.S. team.
(U.S.-Japan-Talks) 
</P>
</TEXT>
