<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy to Visit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. envoy for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke will visit Turkey next week to discuss the
division of the Mediterranean island, the State Department
announced today.
</P>
<P>
It will be his first trip to the region since his appointment
by President Bill Clinton earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, architect of the 1995 agreement to end the Bosnian
war, will be accompanied by Ambassador Thomas Miller, special
coordinator for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said that Holbrooke will
not go to Greece, stressing that the move should not be
interpreted as a slap at Athens.
</P>
<P>
"It is not necessary for an American official of whatever
prominence to go to Greece and Turkey every time they go to the
region," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ankara talks are not a negotiation but a
continuation of discussions Holbrooke and Miller held with Turkish
officials in New York.
</P>
<P>
The two envoys also met recently in New York with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides. They plan to meet with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash later this month in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is expected to meet top political figures on Monday
in Turkey, but the meetings are still being arranged, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"We are engaged in an active process of discussions to see what
assistance we can provide the parties in coming to a conclusion
(on Cyprus). We believe now is the right time to continue the
process in Ankara," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Miller "will discuss the full range of issues
relating to our efforts to promote a settlement of the Cyprus
dispute," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
