<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Scales Down Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The increase in interest rates
and the peso depreciation have forced the Philippine government to
scale down its economic growth targets for this year.
</P>
<P>
The Development Budget Coordinating Committee (DBCC) Friday
approved the reduction of this year's gross national product (GNP)
target from the original 7 to 8 percent to between 5.5 percent and
6 percent. The Philippines' GNP grew by 6.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the gross domestic product (GDP) for 1997 was scaled
down to between 5 and 5.5 percent from the original target of
between 6.1 percent and 6.8 percent, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
GNP is the measure of a country's total production of goods and
services, including income from abroad, while GDP is considered a
more precise measurement of the domestic production of goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
DBCC is an inter-agency committee composed of representatives
of the Department of Finance, the Department of Budget and
Management, the National Economic and Development Authority, the
Central Bank and the Bureau of Treasury.
</P>
<P>
But the committee has not adjusted its inflation target of
between six and seven percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that the changes in the 1997 growth targets were made
assuming an average peso-dollar rate is 28 to 29 pesos:1 for the
whole year and 29.50 to 33.50:1 for the last quarter of the year,
and interest rates are based on the benchmark 91-day Treasury Bill
rate of 12.5 percent average for the whole year and 14.6 percent
for the last quarter.
</P>
<P>
Since early July this year, the Philippine peso has depreciated
about 30 percent against the greenback and Friday's peso-dollar
exchange rate is 33.15:1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
