<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Economy In China's Ethnic Minority Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, October 11 (Xinhua) -- The non-public sector of the
economy in ethnic minority regions in China has grown at an annual
rate of 30 percent in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
By June, the non-state sector of the five autonomous regions of
Guangxi, Inner Mongolia, Ningxia, Tibet, and Xinjiang had assets
of 27 billion yuan (3.25 billion US dollars) and three million
employees.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts say that the growth of the non-state sector has
greatly contributed to the increase of jobs and tax revenues and
the growth of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia, for example, has no limits on size or scope of
business in developing the sector and has set aside special
low-interest loans for private business.
</P>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has arranged one to
three-year tax breaks for private herdsmen in remote areas and has
supported joint ventures or ventures overseas.
</P>
<P>
In the past, non-stated-owned businesses were mainly involved
in small-scale retailing but are now involved in production,
processing, and technology. Many of them co-operate with overseas
partners and export their products.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has also become a major place for laid-off
workers from state-owned enterprises to find work. In Nanning, the
capital of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, they have provided
jobs for 70,000 of the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Private companies in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region have paid
1.83 billion yuan in taxes to the state in the past five years,
while the private sector in Tibet Autonomous Region accounts for
45 percent of the region's total revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
