<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Insurance Policy Issued 46 Years Ago Paid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 11 (Xinhua) -- A life insurance policy so old
that it could have been put into a museum that was discovered in
the northern Chinese port of Tianjin has been paid off by the
People's Insurance Company of China (PICC).
</P>
<P>
The policy was issued by the Tianjin branch of PICC, the
country's largest insurer, in 1951 to Wang Yongbin at a cost of
5,000 yuan (the currency then in use, 10,000 of which are worth
one renminbi yuan now).
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old policy remained unpaid and was found by a PICC
Life agent, who was visiting Wang's nephew, Wang Qinjian, while
trying to sell another policy.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qinjian took the policy out and asked whether it was valid
or not. He was told that that particular life insurance business
was suspended in July, 1959, and that PICC had cleared all
policies.
</P>
<P>
But PICC honored the insurance policy for then 880,000 yuan, and
paid 155.8 renminbi yuan in compensation.
</P>
<P>
China re-opened its insurance companies in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
