<HEADLINE> Panama To Receive Half a Million Tourists in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Half a million tourists are
expected to visit Panama in 1998, Cesar Tribaldos, director
of the Panamanian Tourism Institute (IPAT), said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the director, tourism contributed 443 million
U.S. dollars to the national economy last year, which is the third
biggest generator of international reserves. It is anticipated
that tourism will soon be the country's main source of foreign
currency income.
</P>
<P>
Tribaldos said the country's tourism industry has experienced a
healthy recovery in recent years. He said a number of tourism
projects are being developed in the country with the participation
of Spanish, U.S. and South Korean investors.
</P>
<P>
"Panama will receive more than 470,000 tourists this year from
Europe, the United States and Latin America, a seven percent
increase over 1996," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
