<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Communist Party Central Committee to be Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The 5th Congress of the Cuban
Communist Party (PCC) will reduce its Central Committee members to
150, 70 less than the previous one, announced its Second
Secretary Raul Castro today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced following the vote last night by the
1,500 delegates to the three-day Congress that opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reasons for the reduction, Raul Castro said the
PCC Central Committee must act accordingly with the times,
which demands smaller, more agile and easily convened
administrative organs.
</P>
<P>
He said the newly elected Central Committee must continue the
struggle to overcome the difficult economic problems facing the
country despite the intensification of the U.S. economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
The results of the voting for the formation of the PCC Central
Committee will be known this afternoon. The Central Committee will
also elect the first and second secretary and the rest of the
members of the political bureau.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Castro has been elected PCC first secretary
since the party was founded in the 1960s, and successive
congresses have continued to re-elect him to the post. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
