<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Balance of Trade with U.S. Shows Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian balance of
trade with the United States will show this year the unprecedented
deficit of five billion dollars, the Brazilian Foreign Trade
Association (AEB) said today.
</P>
<P>
The amount is almost half of the total commercial deficit of
Brazil for this year, which will be between 10 billion and 12
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
AEB president Marcus Vinicius Pratini de Moraes said the
deficit shows that Brazil has reached the limit of opening of its
market to U.S. products.
</P>
<P>
Brazil imported last year U.S. products for 11.8 billion
dollars and exported to that country 9.3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek FM Meets Visiting Colombian Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos today met with visiting Colombian Vice President Carlos
Lemos Simmonds to discuss bilateral cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after their talks, Pangalos said that
Athens would back Colombia's participation in the United Nations
Economic and Social Council while Colombia would support Athens in
its bid to join the U.N. security council for the period
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
A framework for bilateral economic and technological
cooperation which had recently been ratified had already begun to
strengthen economic ties between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that an institutional framework was being prepared
to pave the way for closer cooperation between the police forces
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Simmonds said that his country would host an
event featuring Greek culture.
</P>
<P>
Simmonds is visiting Greece on the occasion of a series of
major cultural events being organized here by the Colombian
embassy and the Goulandris Museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Audi Recalls 900,000 Cars Worldwide for Airbag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The German carmaker Audi announced
today that it is recalling over 900,000 Audi model cars worldwide
in order to correct their problematic airbag systems.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of the Audi company, the airbags of
Audi 80, A4, A6 and A8 made in 1995 and 1996 could be accidentally
triggered off by electrostatic discharge when the driver gets in
or out of the car. Several such incidents had already occurred.
</P>
<P>
The problem would be corrected by the Audi company through a
modification in the driving wheel free of charge, the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the company was also recalling the models of Audi 80,
100, 200, V8, Coupe and Cabriolet made in the period from 1988 to
1992 to equip them with more up-to-date and more durable airbag
systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Stand-By Credit for Latvia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved an 18-month stand-by credit for Latvia,
in an amount of about 45 million U.S. dollars equivalent, to
support the government's 1997-1999 economic program.
</P>
<P>
However, the Latvian authorities have indicated their intention
not to draw on the credit as was the case under the recently
expired arrangement.
</P>
<P>
The macroeconomic objectives of the country's 1997-1999
economic program include to achieve real GDP growth of 4 percent
for 1997 and 5 percent for 1998, a reduction in the annual rate of
inflation to 9 percent in 1997 and 7 percent in 1998. They are
also included a narrowing in the external current account deficit
to 6.1 percent of GDP in 1997 and 4.9 percent in 1998. Gross
international reserves will be targeted at the equivalent of some
three months of imports for 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Latvia joined the IMF in May 1992. Its quota is about 126
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF credit currently
totals about 94 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Approve Europol Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The German parliament today passed a
bill giving the country's approve for the creation of a coordinating
centre for police authorities of the European Union member states to
combat rising organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Under a plan envisaged by EU member states, the mandate of the
current Europol drug unit based in the Hague, the Netherlands, would
be expanded from mid-1998 to serve as a central station to collect and
analyze data relating to crimes such as drug trafficking, car
thievery, nuclear smuggling and money laundering in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The analyzed data would then be tranfered to police authorities of
individual EU states to help them track down the criminals.
</P>
<P>
"National police alone are no longer in a position to effectively
fight the cancer of organized crime," said a German parliament member
during the parliament debate today.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the Europol have already been approved by
Britain, Denmark, Spain and Portugal so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Pays Attention to Kids in Armed Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced his appointment today of
Olara Otunnu as his Special Representative for Children in Armed
Conflict, as one of the U.N. steps in helping child victims in
armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, born in Uganda and having held many titles of
international organizations, has been widely recognized for his
long-standing commitment and contribution to diverse activities
relating to international peace and security, prevention of
conflict, and many others, according to the secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
The appointment was actually made September 1. Otunnu will
serve as advocate for the protection of children in conflict
situations, promoting measures and taking concrete initiatives in
particular cases, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
But he has to work on voluntary contributions.
</P>
<P>
Since 1987, an estimated 2 million children have been killed in
armed conflict, according to statistics provided by the United
Nations. Three times that number have been seriously injured or
permanently disabled. Ten million children have been
psychologically traumatized by war, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years alone more than a quarter million
children under the age of 18 have fought as soldiers in 36
conflicts across the world.
</P>
<P>
Today, nearly 30 million children are refugees or internally
displaced because of war in their countries, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The Special Representative for Children in Armed Conflict was
set up in line with a resolution of the U.N. General Assembly in
late 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. leader calls on the international community to pay
greater attention to the problem of war trapped children and do
more for their protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
