<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flight Attendants Suit Against Tobacco Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The secondhand-smoke lawsuit
brought by 60,000 U.S. flight attendants against tobacco industry
was settled today as the industry agreed to pay 300 million U.S.
dollars to establish a research foundation on diseases led by
smoking.
</P>
<P>
The attendants had sued for 5 billion dollars, claiming they
developed lung, heart and other diseases by breathing other
people's smoke on airliners. The trial began four months ago.
</P>
<P>
The settlement marks the first time the tobacco industry agreed
to pay damages in a secondhand-smoke lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
Under the settlement, the nation's four biggest cigarette
makers -- Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co., Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco and Lorillard Inc. -- will finance the Broin
Research Foundation to study cures for illnesses caused by smoke
and to develop early-detection methods.
</P>
<P>
However, the attendants get no money, but under newly agreed-on
terms, they can easily file a claim individually and win. 
</P>
</TEXT>
