<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Villagers Trained to Conserve Wildlife </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Poaching has decreased
in Selous, a well-known game reserve in Tanzania, thanks to the
carrying out of a wildlife conservation program among villagers.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 village game scouts and 150 wildlife committee
members have been trained at the Likuyu community-based wildlife
conservation institute since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The institute principal, Casian Mahundi, said that the
training was aimed at involving villagers in the Selous Game
Reserve catchment areas in order to conserve wildlife, Tanzania
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Likuyu institute, in Songea Rural District, is the only of
its kind in eastern, central and southern Africa providing
training for village game scouts.
</P>
<P>
Courses provided by the institute include wildlife
conservation, forestry, fishing, law and discipline.
</P>
<P>
Mahundi said the training program is part of activities
carried out by the Selous wildlife conservation program jointly
financed by the German and Tanzanian governments.
</P>
<P>
He said the program has benefited Songea and Tunduru in the
Ruvuma Region, Liwale in the Lindi Region and the Morogoro
District.
</P>
<P>
Seeing that poaching has decreased in Selous Game Reserve,
other game reserves and national parks in Tanzania have also
started to send village game scouts to the institute for
training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
