<HEADLINE> Indian Premier Starts Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian Premier Inder Kumar Gujral
arrived here this evening on a two-day visit to Egypt to bolster
bilateral ties, the Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Gujral will meet with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa and Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid,
said MENA.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was accompanied by a high-ranking delegation
that includes the ministers of foreign affairs, tourism,
parliamentary affairs, and mining and steel.
</P>
<P>
In an interview Thursday with the Egyptian daily Al Akhbar,
Gujral said he will discuss with Mubarak on ways to shore up
cooperation in agriculture, food security, bio-technology, energy,
information, water resources, computer program and to set up joint
industrial ventures.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the two sides will sign three cooperation
agreements in the fields of tourism, customs and culture. And
preparations are under way to stage an exhibition of Indian
products in Cairo next April.
</P>
<P>
India has so far invested a total of 330 million U.S. dollars
in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Besides, regional and international issues such as the Mideast
peace process, Indian-Pakistani relations, disarmament, reform of
the United Nations and revival of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
are also on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
India and Egypt played a vital role in the founding of the
NAM. A preparatory meeting in Cairo in June 1961 led to its
establishment two months later.
</P>
<P>
The Indian premier is on an African tour which has so far taken
him to Uganda and South Africa. 
</P>
