<HEADLINE> Early marriage prevalent in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 10 (Xinhua) -- About 31 percent of the 15-19
age group of Zambian girls have eighter given birth or are
pregnant, the Family Life Movement of Zambia said today.
</P>
<P>
It added that some as young as 10-year-old girls have gone
into marriage due to economic hardships, changing traditional
patterns and rapid urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Expressing her concern representative of the organization
Mwape Lubilo said in Kabwe, central Zambia today that early
marriage is leading to pregnancy, child bearing and illness such
as sexually transmitted (STD) diseases and HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In a paper on "child, adolescent and youth development"
presented to a five-day workshop to discuss population, gender
and development advocacy, she said it is sad that early marriage
is an issue calling for urgent discussions.
</P>
<P>
The statutory law indicates legal marriage age at 18 years,
while on the contrary, the customary law pegs it at attainment of
puberty, she said.
</P>
<P>
There is an urgent need to harmonize the statutory and
customary laws in order to protect the girl-child, Lubilo said.
</P>
<P>
On abortion, she said available data shows that
inaccessibility to legal and safe abortions is a major cause of
maternal morbidity and mortality.
</P>
<P>
While friends, elders and sometimes herbalists are expected to
help in inducing abortion, recent data indicates that young
people could induce an abortion themselves, she said.
</P>
<P>
"A study conducted in four districts in Western Province
indicates that 12 percent of females in the age group 11-19 had
already experienced an illegal abortion without recording any
form of help," she said.
</P>
<P>
Lubilo said 17 out of 1,000 people in Zambia have an SDT such
as gonorrhoea, syphilis and herpes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
