<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Portugal Sign Pact on Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mozambique
and Portugal today signed an agreement on water conservancy
cooperation, under which the latter will assist Mozambique in
managing its international rivers.
</P>
<P>
Roberto White, Mozambican Minister of Public Works and
Housing, and Ricardo Magalhaes, Portuguese Secretary of State of
Natural Resources sealed the pact on behalf of their respective
governments.
</P>
<P>
The accord stipulates that four more projects of water
conservancy will be implemented in Mozambique, with a budget of
1.65 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, White expressed the hope that such
cooperation be extended to the repairing of water supply
infrastructure in both urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Magalhaes, on his part, noted that besides offering support to
Mozambique in managing international rivers, what jumps to
immediate attention is dam safety, the development of Monapo
river valley in Namula province in the north, research on Zambeze
river's exit to the sea as well as the training for Mozambican
technicians.
</P>
<P>
According to the Portuguese official, both countries are
located in the lower reaches of international rivers, and faced
with complicated management problem. Portugal, however, can offer
Mozambique references with its own experiences and legal means.
</P>
<P>
Magalhaes arrived in Maputo on Wednesday and is expected to
conclude his visit here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
