<HEADLINE> Greece Warns Turkey Over Cyprus Missiles Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece today warned Turkey that
any attack by Ankara against a Greek vessel would be regarded as a
cause for war.
</P>
<P>
The warning was sent out today by Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas when asked to comment on statements by Russia's
ambassador in Cyprus, who said that his country would consider as
a "casus belli" a Turkish strike against any Russian ship
transporting S-300 surface-to-air missiles to Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
"The same holds if a Greek vessel is attacked," Reppas said,
but added that he did not believe such a development was likely
"since everything is quite legal and in line with the interests
which any government would want to protect."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Turkey's aggressive designs and
statements regarding strikes against the vessels of other
countries were putting a strain on good relations between
countries.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, Cyprus and Russia signed an agreement
under which Nicosia will purchase Russian-made S-300 ground-to-air
missiles to bolster the defense of the island republic.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has voiced its opposition to such a decision by Cyprus,
warning it would take all measures possible to stop the island
from deploying the missiles. 
</P>
