<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 971034fff French FM Reiterates Country's African Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine said today pledged his country's renewed
commitment in Africa, saying France will not get involved in
Africa's internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
France will give methodical support to the consolidation of
the foundation of the rule of law, the process of
democratization, good governance, and will be in favor of
sustainable development, which is the key to stability and peace
in Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when addressing African ambassadors to the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) here at the Africa hall this
evening.
</P>
<P>
"For several years now, Africa has offered growing
confirmation with each day of their determination to be active in
preventing and settling the conflicts that beset it," Vedrine
said.
</P>
<P>
"To enable the OAU to respond to the many emergencies more
effectively, France made a first contribution in November 1996 of
a million Francs to the mechanism for conflict prevention,
management and resolution," the minister added with an
announcement that France would contribute one million US dollars
to the OAU in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Referring to peace-keeping operations in Africa, Vedrine said
"France intends next year to devote more than 30 million dollars
to training and equipment activities aimed at improving African
peace-keeping capabilities."
</P>
<P>
France "consistently supports maintaining significant flows of
aid" to Africa, the foreign minister said, adding that because
France "is convinced that there can be no lasting stabilization
in Africa without development, and although it is first and
foremost up to the Africans to find in themselves the dynamics of
development, the international community has an obligation to
help them in this endeavor."
</P>
<P>
As a permanent member of the UN Security Council, he said,
France has been working unremittingly to help prevent crises,
favoring more and more a multi-lateral approach to questions of
security on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
France "has, on a number of occasions demonstrated its refusal
to let itself be drawn into internal conflicts or to interfere in
the internal affairs of its African partners, as it did in the
Congo Brazzaville crisis where it supports the international
mediation of President Bongo and of Mr. Mohammed Sahnoun," adding
that "about Comoro islands, France supports the mediation of
Ambassador Yere under the mandate of OAU."
</P>
<P>
The French foreign minister is currently on an African tour.
He visited South Africa Thursday and will visit Cote d'Ivoire
tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Hails Nobel Peace Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan official today
hailed Nobel Peace Prize as being awarded to the international
campaigner for land mine clearance, saying it is a world
recognition.
</P>
<P>
Helder Cruz, head of Angola's National Institute for Removing
Obstacles and Explosives, said the decision is very correct,
since land mine clearance is a major event which has far-reaching
significance.
</P>
<P>
The decision will inspire the international community to make
continuous efforts in ridding the whole world of land mines, Cruz
added.
</P>
<P>
This year's Nobel Peace Prize has been given to the
international campaign for land mine clearance and its
coordinator Jody Williams.
</P>
<P>
This is also an encouragement to the Angolan government for
eliminating land mines, Cruz said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Angola has made great contributions to
clearing mines and educating its people of the danger of land
mines, and Angola will make further efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Angola is among the countries in the world which have a great
many land mines planted during the civil war. United Nations
statistics show that there are over 13 million land mines planted
in Angola, which has great impact on the country's rehabilitation
after a civil war of nearly two decades. 
</P>
