<HEADLINE> Hundreds of PKK Rebels Killed in Turkish Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's government troops have
killed 764 outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) militants in the
operations in northern Iraq since late last month, the Anatolia
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by the Turkish General Staff, which said
that at the same time 33 other PKK rebels were captured and 17
surrendered. It did not mention casualties of the government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 15,000 Turkish troops, backed by jets and
artillery fire, launched cross-border operations in northern Iraq
to wipe out the PKK camps there.
</P>
<P>
Senior Turkish military sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that Turkish troops had taken much of northern
Iraq under control through the three-week-long operations.
</P>
<P>
Describing the PKK as a threat to its border security, Turkey
said its latest operations in northern Iraq were aimed to prevent
the PKK militants from infiltrating into southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing offensive against the PKK rebels is "a limited and
routine action," it added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has frequently launched military operations in northern
Iraq in the past two years to strike the PKK militants, who have
been fighting a 13-year-old war against the Turkish government for
an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In spite of Ankara's efforts to play down the operations, Iran
and some Arab countries have condemned Turkey for violating Iraq's
sovereignty and territorial integrity, demanding an immediate
withdrawal of Turkish troops from the region.
</P>
<P>
A London-based Kurdish television reported Thursday that some
units of the Turkish troops had pulled out of northern Iraq. But
neither the Turkish Foreign Ministry nor its General Staff has
confirmed the reports.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has been disturbed by the PKK rebels who adopted a
hit-and-run tactic and often sought shelter in northern Iraq
during massive Turkish government troop offensives.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent as many as 50,000 troops into northern Iraq last
May, dealing a heavy blow to the militants there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
