<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Announces Missile Sales to Greece, Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon announced today
it would sell advanced air-launched missiles to Turkey and Greece,
two rivals who are both American allies in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Greece would buy 20 Harpoon anti-ship missiles for 35 million
U.S. dollars, and both Greece and Turkey would get Advanced
Medium-range Air-to-Air Missiles (AMRAAM) anti-aircraft missiles,
Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
Greece would pay 42 million U.S. dollars for 90 AMRAAMs, Turkey
62 million U.S. dollars for 138 missiles.
</P>
<P>
The sales will go ahead unless Congress acts to stop them.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon said the sales "will not adversely affect either the
military balance in the region or U.S. efforts to encourage a
negotiated settlement of the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an island in the the Mediterranean Sea, has been
divided since 1974, when Turkey sent in troops to protect the
Turkish minority after a failed coup by Greek officers seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey claims Greece is threatening regional peace by
supporting plans of Cyprus' Greek-led government to deploy
Russian-made air defense missiles that could reach Turkey's
southern coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
