<HEADLINE> Cameroon's Ruling Party Opens Up New Visions for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The national bureau of the
women's wing of the ruling Cameroun People's Democratic Movement
(WCPDM) published a manifesto for women recently, opening up new
visions for women, local paper Cameroun Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto outlines what the Camerounian has gained and
will gain under the WCPDM's presidential candidate Paul Biya in
the seven years ahead.
</P>
<P>
It envisions strategies for the attainment of these "global
objectives" such as improving the living conditions of women,
giving greater concern on the legal status of women and the
valorization of feminine human resources in all sectors of
development.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto also includes the effective participation of
women in decision making, the fight against violence to women and
the improvement of the official set-up integration of women in
development.
</P>
<P>
The manifesto is optimistic that these strategies, when
implemented, will take the Camerounian women well into a
promising 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Biya, the presidential candidate, has pledged and intended to
"overcome the causes of poverty among disabled people, increase
women's literacy vote by 70 percent and increase information and
communication on woman and development," said the manifesto.
</P>
</TEXT>
