<HEADLINE> US CEOs Expect Slower Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Chief executives from some
of the U.S. largest companies expect the economy to lose some
steam but many say their own firms have yet to cool down, The Wall
Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the biannual survey of the U.S. Business Council, a trade
group that represents the biggest U.S. companies, more than three
quarters of the CEOs said that they think the economy will ease to
a moderate growth of 2 percent to 2.75 percent through the middle
of next year.
</P>
<P>
That is significantly slower than the U.S. economy's 4.1
percent growth rate in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
However, 11 percent reported that their own company's business
is more tepid now than three to six months ago, while 34 percent
said that their business is stronger.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that more than three-quarters of them said
they are having a hard time finding "competent workers", a problem
affecting their location decisions and expansion plans.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80 percent of the leaders were operating with a leaner
work force and 68 percent were trying to find better ways to
retain employees, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
But only 35 percent of the CEOs said they are paying more to
get the workers they want and about half expect that wages and
salaries will rise no faster next year than they have this year.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that a slight majority of CEOs said the U.S.
interest rate will be higher by the middle of next year while
nearly half of them expect the dollar to be lower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
