<HEADLINE> Turkey to Build Trans-Continental Railway Tunnel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has planned to build a
trans-continental railway tunnel in its largest city of Istanbul
in a bid to relieve the growing traffic pressure across the
Bosphorus Strait.
</P>
<P>
The tunnel, linking Asia and Europe, has been approved by the
the cabinet, said Minister of Transportation Necdet Menzir today.
</P>
<P>
"This project will significantly contribute to solutions to
the transportation, traffic and environmental problems of
Istanbul," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister expected that the tunnel would be completed in
four years time.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government earlier proposed a third bridge over the
Bosphrous Strait for it was easier and quicker to build but
dropped the plan in the face of strong opposition from the public
who complained it would change the city's skyline.
</P>
<P>
There have already been two bridges, the Bosphrous Bridge and
the Fatih Sultan Mehmet Bridge, across the strait. But they are
becoming more and more limited in capacity for vehicles running on
them between Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The population of Istanbul, Turkey's commercial and
transportation center, has been increasing quickly due to large
numbers of migrants from the underdeveloped eastern and
southeastern Turkey, bringing huge pressure on urban traffic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
