<DOCNO> XIE19971011.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Japanese Talks over Trade Barriers Conclude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Japan
ended their annual review of a 1995 auto trade agreement with the
U.S. side expressing disappointment over the lack of progress for
enhancing exports of U.S.-made cars and parts.
</P>
<P>
During the 3-day talks, the United States had presented a
series of proposals on ways that Japan could speed efforts to
remove barriers to sales of both cars and auto parts, said Wendy
Cutler, assistant U.S. Trade Representative who led the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposals included further deregulation of the auto
repair market as a way of boosting sales of U.S.-made brakes and
other replacement parts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. auto companies have urged the Clinton administration
to launch a process that could lead to U.S. trade sanctions if
Japan does not speed up its deregulation process.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held in San Francisco and included the
participation of trade officials from the 15-nation European
Union, Canada and Australia as observers.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the United States reached agreement in June 1995 on a
five-year program to expand sales of American and other
foreign-made cars and parts with an annual review required to
monitor progress.
</P>
<P>
Last year sales of U.S. cars in Japan did increase by 34
percent, but sales in the first eight months of this year have
declined by 19 percent. The U.S. overall trade deficit with Japan
has begun to widen after two years of improvement and is running
at an annual rate of 53 billion U.S. dollars, up from a 1996
deficit of 48 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
